<HEAD>

<TITLE>Practical Tips</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>



<IMG SRC="images/folio.gif" ALT="GreenBeat!" ALIGN=top WIDTH=456 HEIGHT=72><BR>
<P>



<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Practical Tips for Choosing</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>the Right College</FONT><P>
by Miriam Weinstein<BR> 
editor, Making A Difference College Guide: Outstanding Colleges to Help You 
Make A Better World<BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
<font size=+1>



What should you look for in a college if you want to use your education to find
meaningful work and to make a better world?  There are several different aspects you may
want to investigate follow. 
<P>
Does the college have a mission statement? Read it -
some talk about turning out educate d students, others talk about turning out
compassionate citizens. Quaker and Mennonite  colleges have long-standing
concerns for peace and social justice. 
<P>
Look at the majors offered. If the school
does not have an environmental studies department, you may well wonder what day
and age the school is living in. Do note that some colleges  have a geography or
biology major that is quite akin to environmental studies. Check further by
giving the career office a call - and see what lines  of work students are g oing
in to.
<P>
Look for majors such as urban planning, public health, forestry, social work,
peace studies,  conservation biology, women's studies, ethnic studies, or
science, technology & values. Consider a school with enough  relevant majors to
be sure it really ca res about preparing you for meaningful work. 
<P>
Next, get a
hold of the catalog. Look at  the required courses (if any.) Are they English 1,
Economic 1, and Political Science 1? Or are there interdisciplinary freshman and
sophomore seminars and courses such as "Moral and Ethical Decisions in Public
Life", "Prejudice, Discrimination and Responsibility,"  or "World Hunger" 
offered? While many outstanding colleges might not  offer seminars such as these,
you will see that interdisciplinary education is very prominent, and that often
you can design an major of your own choosing. 
<P>
Look at the contents of the
courses in the majors that  sound of interest to you. Courses in the economics
department give a lot of insight into the spirit of a college. Do you find mo
stly business oriented courses on "International Investment," "Macroeconomics
101," "Money, Credit and Banking" or  "Economics of Natural Resources,"
"Economics of Health," " Political Economy, "  "Economics of Labor." You have
just learned whether the c ourses offer a relevant social analysis. 
<P>
The
religious studies department can also be very telling - how many of the worlds
religions are incorporated - and in what depth? Now you've glimpsed if the
school's perspective is global, and how sensitive it is to today's increasingly
multicultural society. 
<P>
Does the school have an explicit concern for the
environment, reflected in a high percentage of environmentally related courses?
If it lists an environmental major - but the catalog just cross-references you to
other departments, I think you can justifiably be concerned about the importance
of the department to the administration.
<P>
Does the school have a strong service ethic?  The national rate of community
service at colleges is still under 5%. At a "Making A Difference" college, you
will usually  find  at least 30% of students doing community service. 
<P>
How
supportive is the colleg e -- is there a well-funded office coordinating and
promoting service? Is it staffed 5 hours a week or 40?  Even more essential,
does the school offer service-learning programs -  a blossoming new area in higher
education, where students go out into the re al world, and do real work, at the
request of local communities, and integrate their learning and their work while 
receiving full credit. So, for a course in  say "Economics of Poverty" you
might work with children at a school in a low-income neighborh ood.
<P>
Does the college offer or is it affiliated with international service-learning
programs which enable you to receive credit for working in poor countries at the
local level  - living with villagers rather than in dorms, and helping to design
a sustainable agricultural system,  or build a water cistern so  children can
attend school. 
<P>
This is also called experiential education  - and it's considered
the most effective form of learning because it makes your learning vital, and
engaged in the real world - wit h you as an active participant. You may easily
forget what you read in a textbook, you won't so quickly forget being out "in the
field"  working in a health clinic in the mountains of Ecuador. 
<P>
Does the school have a strong internship program? Internships not only give you
job experience so necessary today, but enable you to see if the field you are
considering working in is really a good fit. Many students find a job offer
waiting for them upo n graduation from agency  for which they worked.
<P>
If you think that spending your life trying to make a better world means a life
of financial struggle, think again. Not only can graduates find interesting
employment opportunities, with good starting salaries, in some fields the
employment opportunities are way above average. 
<P>
In today's job market you are as
likely to get as high a starting salary in  policy planning or gerontology (the
study of the elderly) as in law! 
<P>
Forest engineering graduates find 100%
employment - while civil engineers are having a tough time finding any placement.
 Furthermore, when your work is personally meaningful to you, you will be happier
. 
<P>
Personal satisfaction is something which no high salary can buy. Law students
are turning increasingly to public interest law instead o f corporate law - not
only because it's where the jobs are today, but also because it's where their
hearts are. Non-profits are hiring all over the country - and some of them even
help repay a students college loans.
<P>
For
many top students there seems to be an automatic thought process about which
colleges to apply to: either your local college or state university, or the most
selective big name schools. Consider looking further - the best education for you
may be found elsewhere. Often it is to your advantage to be a big fish in a
medium or small bowl, rather than a medium fish is a big bowl. 
<P>
At universities
and prestigious institutions, professors are hired for their research. While they
may be brilliant in their fields, being a brilliant researcher hasn't yet been
shown to correlate with being a brilliant professor. And if you are at a
university, these professors seldom teach on the undergraduate level.
<P>
Check out
the size of freshman lecture halls at universities - they can be from 100 to even
400 students, and frequently taught by graduate students. And accessible
professors? Well - maybe if you are the star student. On the other hand,
universities can offer a mind-boggling array of majors, greater opportunities to
participate in advanced res earch (although usually for graduate students) and
vast resources.
<P>
Many of the lesser known colleges may offer
you more of what you are looking for. Small classes (sometimes 8 to 10 students,)
accessible professors hired for their teaching ability, an administration and
faculty that share your values, and an innovative, caring and responsive
institution. At a small  or medium size college (and I define medium as under
3,000 students, small as under 1,000 students) you are unlikely to fall through
the cracks. 
<P>
Be aware that if you are considering graduate school, you'll find
they are often more interested in the person who graduates at the top of the
class than the person in the middle - regardless of the institution.
<P>

</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=1>
