<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, <<Enter DATE Here>>, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #4 (Volume 1, No. 3)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 3<BR>Article #4</H1></CENTER>

<H2>BOOK REVIEW</H2>

<H4>Emberley, P.C. and Newell, W.R. (1994): Bankrupt Education: The Decline of
Liberal Education in Canada.</H4>

<P><I>-Reviewed by Roxanne McDiarmid, Ed. D.</I></P>

<P>A clarion call to Canadian consciousness is being sounded by Peter C.
Emberley and Waller R. Newell in their book Bankrupt Education: The Decline
of Liberal Education in Canada.  They register deep concern for fact that
in direct opposition to the inspirational guidelines and organizational
structures for liberal education in Canadian schools and universities,
constituted by Canada's founding politicians and educators, a massive
restructuring initiative to disrupt those footings is currently being
foisted upon a largely unsuspecting Canadian public.</P>

<P>Premised on an ideology of victimization, unanswerable allegations of
systemic racism and classism, allow the reformers a virtual open court in
which to hurl their process of endless alterations and renovations.  The
authors describe how in Ontario, in 1992 for example, the Ministry of
Education issued directives to school boards to develop and put in place
Ministry approved anti-racism and ethno-cultural equity policies in short
order.  Immediately behind this posturing followed two new policy documents
which appear intended to divest Ontario schools of every last remnant of
the liberal education for which many senior citizens now yearn.</P>

<P>The initiatives focused on The Transition Years: Grades 7,8, and 9, and
were marked by the features of de-streaming of students, learning outcomes
with their accompanying benchmark assessment procedures, and The Common
Curriculum.  The Core programme content of The Common Curriculum was
organized into four integrated subject modules: namely, Language; Arts;
Self and Society; and Mathematics, Science and Technology; all of which was
intended to promote self-actualization, rather than fine character and
citizenship as liberal education had offered in the past.</P>

<P>Based  upon assumptions of enlightened entitlement, and propelled by
convictions of logical self-certainty, resourcefulness, creativity and
adaptability, today's student, Emberley and Newell explain, is expected to
be a self-directed learner at the centre of his or her universe.  The "new"
students are to use their 'innate' set of linguistic and thinking skills to
problem-solve their way through the 'holism' of this system, which they are
to believe is their real world (pp. 44-45).  The authors contend however,
that The Common Curriculum is not a balanced curriculum because it does not
harmonize identity with difference as did that which characterized the soul
of a liberally educated person.  Nor does The Common Curriculum succeed,
they claim, in trying to conjoin universal skill with self-empowerment and
ethno-cultural identities, because here it simply bypasses the institutions
normally understood to mediate between the real world and the individual.
The actual result, the authors suggest, reflects a bland homogeneity
distinguished only by mediocrity.</P>

<P>Emberley and Newell advise that by gnostic insistence on the superiority
of their 'new' ideas over all traditional practice, today's social
reformers are merely the 1990s version of progressive activists with
similar agendas from earlier decades.  For example: 'values education' in
the 1960s, 'enriched courses' in the 1970s, and 'back-to-basics' in the
1980s.  Emberley discusses this rationale in depth in his recent book,
Values Education and Technology: The Ideology of Dispossession.<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A></P>

<P>Over the past thirty years, Emberley and Newell tell us, 'child-centred
and process-orientated' concepts of teaching and learning have been putting
students in Canada at an ever-increasing disadvantage when they enter
university, by having failed to equip learners with the basic skills of
reading, writing and analytical self-distance.  In addition, by publicizing
censorious views of university management, teaching and research practices,
the reconstructionists attempt to erode the public's confidence in the
aspiration to impartiality, the very purpose for which the university was
founded.  True independent-mindedness is the highest ideal of
liberal education the authors remind us, and thus indispensable to a
university's identity (p. 67).</P>

<P>Lying at the root of the reformers' relentless negation of education for
reality, is their general fear and abandonment of standards of merit.
Emberley and Newell  believe that rewarding and encouraging merit in
individuals contributes naturally to the development of a just,
hierarchical society.  It promotes a genuine intellectual diversity that
prepares dutiful citizens and leaders for the community.  Germane to the
constitution of the Canadian confederation was our unique history in the
accommodation of the duties and rights of individuals, to be ensured by an
education toward those goals.</P>

<P>Bankrupt Education provides the readers with an encapsulated odyssey of
liberal education's history and heroes of the Western tradition.  A glimpse
is given of that wider window into the world, which was modified over
centuries to remain vital in its goal to seek a truly judicious balance in
the learner, between the human longing for wholeness and its relation to
the principles of a just and satisfying political order.  By the reading of
great books, the liberal student learned first through Plato's Socratic
soul-craft, the arts of physical fitness and dialectical speech, and then
from Aristotle's civic paideia  the need for citizens to understand
themselves in the immediacy of their everyday communal lives.  The study of
gymnastics, mathematics, poetry, art and drama, originated this curriculum.
Later, the study of works by poets like Dante and Shakespeare expanded the
student's horizons while maintaining local patriotism, the classical virtue
of which would be further enriched by Biblical studies and Augustine's
distinctive Christian teaching of humility in God's Love.  The traditional
teacher-student relationship of instruction and debate promised to ensure
the continuance of this heritage.</P>

<P>Characterized by the questioning of tradition and practice, liberal
learning increasingly disquieted established orders of knowledge in Europe
from the Middle Ages, as it continually sought to reconcile immediacy with
transcendence.  Gradually, the previously integrated human soul became
wrenched apart with the advancement of the modern self-evident logic
developed in Cartesian mathematical thinking. The idyllic idealism of
Enlight-enment philosophies allowed the erotic longings of the heart to
escape into a world of Rousseauean dreams while they longed to be free of
the severity of the analytical mind.  In today's schooling, where
infatuation with information from these disparate perceptions reigns
supreme, therapeutic group encounters of self-disclosure now masquerade as
teaching and learning classrooms.</P>

<P>Most important for Canadian students, the authors advise, is that they
learn through a broad reading of historical and philosophical works, that
the first principles of revolutionary optimism for individual freedom
emanated from the opposing extremes of formalism and romanticism, and
animated the founders of the United States.  By contrast, Canada's
constitution was established on principles informed by precedent and
tradition.  It issues from a cardinal concern for the common good,
requiring renewal by an education in appreciation of organic ties.  United
in their dedication to oppose scientism, utilitarianism, empiricism and
pragmatism, the architects of Canadian education insisted that the common
sense endowed to human beings would be improved through the learning of
virtue, so that moral principle and public duty must take precedence over
individual rights and autonomy.</P>

<P>Consequently, if Canada is to survive the increasing universalization and
atomization which are presently putting the  nation-state at peril on a
global scale, Emberley and Newell advise that we must restore Canadian
liberal education.  The best promise for sustaining the distinctive
Canadian capacity to harmonize cultural difference with genuine human
longing for a higher Unity rests with a very different education curriculum
than the one currently offered.<BR></P>

<P><A NAME=1><SUP>1</SUP></A> Emberley, P.C. (1995), Values Education and Technology:<BR>
The Ideology of Dispossession. University of Toronto Press.</P>

<H4>Roxanne McDiarmid was a teacher for 38 years in the Ontario public school
system.  She recently completed her doctorate at the Ontario Institute for
Studies in Education.</H4>

