<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #3 (Volume 1, No. 2)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 2<BR>
Article #3</H1></CENTER>

<H2>BOOK REVIEW</H2>

<H4>Gertrude Himmelfarb: The De-Moralization of Society: Victorian Virtues to

Modern Values (New York: Alfred Knopf, 1995) 306pp. $33.50 (Can.)</H4>



<P><I>-Reviewed by Professor Graeme Hunter</I></P>



<P>Gertrude Himmelfarb's superb tract for these times is about the

"de-moralization" of society, in both senses of the term. We are

'de-moralized' because we are no longer able to think of our lives (much

less live them) in moral terms. And we are demoralized - that is, defeated,

discouraged, dismayed - by the effects of the revolutionary,

counter-cultural ideas that enchanted us only thirty years ago.</P>



<P>Despite the expectation raised by her sub-title, "From Victorian Virtues

to Modern Values", Himmelfarb does not exactly offer a history of the last

hundred years of moral reflection. Instead, all seven chapters are devoted

to vignettes, stories and historical narrative concerning Victorian

Britain, with occasional sidelong glances at the U.S.A. in the same period.

Victorian attitudes to the poor, to Jews and to women are all canvassed,

but mainly Himmelfarb is interested by what we would call their 'family

values'. What she calls 'modern values', and the de-moralized society that

goes with them, are discussed only in the prologue, epilogue and postscript

of the book.</P>



<P>It is surprising that so uneven an allotment of pages turns out so well,

but two things work in the author's favour. First, she is aided by her

obvious mastery of the Victorian period, which enables her to pick the most

telling examples and apposite illustrations of her main contentions. Next,

the portrait of Victorian times is not painted for its own sake, but rather

in the way that the deeds of a    virtuous older sister might be praised in

the hearing of a wayward child. Thus the focus of the book turns out to be

contemporary North America after all, even when it is most concerned with

Victorian Britain.</P>



<P>No comment is necessary, for example, when prominent Victorians refer to

the Queen as "the head of  morality" or praise the Royal Family's "salutary

influence" on the nation's morals. Likewise, our feminist 'herstorians',

prepared to reject the entire past as a time of unrelieved oppression, will

no doubt appreciate the unspoken message tucked away in a footnote:

"Throughout the nineteenth century more novels were published by women

(under their own names) than by men."</P>



<P>And so it goes throughout the book. The picture of Victorians as

materialistic, hypocritical, overly acquisitive, and sexually repressed

gives way to a more balanced account of more believable people. They turn

out to be men and women to whom giving is as important as gaining, who

sought (and often found) sexual satisfaction in marriage, and whose

hypocrisy is more in the eye of the twentieth century beholder (comparing

their deeds with our thoughts) than in any documentable weakness of their

own. Himmelfarb shows us people for whom admiration would be more fitting

than scorn.</P>



<P>Those who find this approach to Kulturkritik too subtle may wish to turn

immediately to the epilogue, where the knockout blows are quickly struck.

The illegitimacy rate in London's poorest quarter was under 3% in 1900

and had not risen above 5% by 1960. By 1992 it had reached 32%. Similar

figures apply in the United States, except that for blacks they must be

roughly doubled. Homicide and violent crime have followed a similar upward

path, as have drug addiction and alcoholism, especially among the young.</P>



<P>Take a walk through the older part of your town and compare those grand

Victorian houses with the cheap vaults in which middle class people store

themselves today. That will put you in the proper frame of mind for reading

Himmelfarb's book, something everyone who can exercise moral influence upon

our sick society should be sure to do.<BR></P>



<H4>Professor Graeme Hunter is Professor of Philosophy at the University of Ottawa<BR>

and is a member of the Centre's Research Council.</H4>



<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>



<A NAME=Noll><H4>Mark A. Noll: The Scandal of the Evangelical Mind (Grand Rapids: Eerdmans,

1994). 279 pp, $28.00 (Can.)</H4>



<P><I>-Reviewed by Professor Graeme Hunter</I></P>



<P>"The search for a Christian mind is not, in the end, a search for mind, but

a search for God." On this surprising note Mark Noll ends his timely

exhortation to Evangelicals to think. It is surprising because Noll seems

to have been telling us with exemplary clarity up to that point that

evangelicals have a different problem: They have already and indisputably

found God; their problem is that they have found Him without engaging their

minds. The real message of Noll's book therefore seems to be twofold:

First, evangelicals can no longer afford to do without their minds. Second,

some of them, like Noll himself, are beginning to realize that.</P>



<P>Mark Noll is the McManis Professor of Christian Thought at Wheaton

College, and so has a vested interest in multiplying thinking evangelicals.

That he also has the capacity to do so is demonstrated by this learned,

lucid book. The manifold intellectual failings and few successes of recent

evangelicalism, documented here with both passion and attention to detail,

make a sad story, but not a hopeless one. Noll describes his book as "an

epistle from a wounded lover". He convincingly argues that it is in the

interest of the whole Church to see a Christian mind develop in the

spiritually dynamic, numerically strong,     but intellectually sluggish

giant of evangelicalism.</P>



<P>When Charles Malik opened the Billy Graham Center at Wheaton College in

1980, he asked his audience a couple of provocative questions. "Who among

the evangelicals can stand up to the great secular or naturalistic or

atheistic scholars on their own terms of scholarship or research? Who among

the evangelical scholars is quoted as a normative source by the greatest

secular authorities on history or philosophy or psychology or sociology or

politics?" Any informed reader will easily supply Malik's implied answer.</P>



<P>The Scandal of the Evangelical Mind documents the scandalous fact that

there is almost no evangelical mind. The Christians most in need of

intellectual awakening continue in the soundest sleep. Yet the book itself

is evidence that their torpor may be ending. Noll is an evangelical writer

who knows his craft as well as his subject and he gives a reasoned,

compelling account of the history and current state of the evangelical

constituency within North American Protestantism.</P>



<P>The mental complacency of today's evangelicals apparently derives from the

intellectual successes of their ancestors. In the middle of the last

century Protestant thinkers found themselves broadly in sympathy with the

major intellectual currents of their day. They were empiricists in science,

common-sensical in philosophy, intuitivists in morality, and biblicists in

dogma. In social matters they were pragmatic and activist, viewing the

world with the expansive confidence which we now see as typical of their

age.</P>



<P>It didn't last, however.  When the dominant scientific paradigms changed,

many Protestant intellectuals either couldn't or wouldn't change with them.

Increasingly, therefore, they found themselves at odds with the scientific

community and threatened by it. Pragmatic and activist social policy was

unaffected, while the thought that had once guided it was transformed into

dogma. Gradually, a noticeably anti-intellectual constituency began to form

within the Protestant churches.</P>



<P>Politically, for example, contemporary evangelicals are not known for any

penetrating analysis of political life, but for their activism,

particularly concerning abortion. (That they are active in a just and good

cause is true, but not germane to the question of their intellectual

achievements.) In science they are associated not with mainstream

discoveries or novel technological applications, but with the creationist

alternative to mainstream science. In different ways and to different

degrees both their politics and their science make valuable contributions

to contemporary Christian life. Noll's point is only that they are not

intellectual contributions. He grants, of course, that the intellect is not

the only faculty or even the most important one. But it exists. And our

Lord called upon us to use it in his service. Evangelicals therefore will

neglect to do so at their peril.</P>



<P>Of course, the moral of the tale applies widely, and Noll's study will

therefore be read with interest and   profit by members of all

denominations. No part of the Church can expect to exert much influence on

an impatient, pluralistic America, if its only resources are its own

intuitions, however well-justified, and common sensical these may be. There

is no way to dispense with the currencies of culture and science.  The only

way to use them effectively is for Christians to buy them, melt them down,

and then mint them afresh, stamped with the image of Christ. This

invigorating call to intellectual action from an awakened evangelical may

be the leaven needed for the whole lump.</P>



<P>Less convincing is Noll's contention that the so-called

"anti-foundationalist" and anti-realist thinking, which he detects and

encourages in some recent evangelical thought, will bring the evangelical

mind far along the road to recovery. The common-sense heritage of

evangelicals might link more easily and profitably with the resurgent

scientific and moral realism of recent years. In any case, Noll's excellent

book is likely to influence the development of the evangelical mind for

years to come and deserves the widest discussion.<BR></P>



<H4>Professor Graeme Hunter is Professor of Philosophy at the University of Ottawa.<BR>

He is a member of the Centre's Research Council.</H4>

<CENTER>
