<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #1 (Volume 1, No. 1)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 1<BR>
Article #1</H1></CENTER>

<H2>A tree without roots cannot stand</H2>



<H3>Some aspects of a problem at the root of Canadian society and what the

Centre proposes to do about it.</H3>



<P><I>Iain T. Benson<BR>

Senior Research Fellow, Centre for Renewal in Public Policy, Ottawa</I></P>



<P>In his recently published Massey Lectures, the Canadian philosopher Charles

Taylor writes about "The Malaise of Modernity".  To suffer a malaise is to

be uncomfortable and indicators in many areas point to wide-spread

uneasiness in Canadian society.  We were not educated in the tradition of

the virtues and, consequently, have a more or less fragmentary sense of

what the good is on the personal or social level.  A shift of this

magnitude has had and continues to have massive consequences in society

affecting every aspect of our lives.  To take one example, courts have

recently accepted a "community standards" test as the basis for determining

whether pornography is obscene under the Criminal Code.  Unless the

standard is itself connected to a meaningful moral framework, this seems to

decide what way the ship should go by following the direction in which the

bow is pointing: not a recommended form of navigation.</P>



<P>In every discipline, every area of life, people continue to function in

their day to day work and in their families according to principles that

have their roots in our philosophical and theological traditions.  Yet, at

the same time, an increasing number (or an increasing number of those in positions of influence) claim that these principles are merely veils for power or are based on outmoded

or incorrect notions.  Such people then select principles that appeal to them and give no

reasoned basis for choosing certain standards from traditional morality while rejecting others.  This is the impasse of modernity.</P>



<P>And all the while Royal Commissions on this or that key subject continue to

churn out Reports and Studies; judges pronounce their decisions on this or

that important aspect of the law; academics produce their books and

articles on important questions; doctors continue to examine and prescribe for their patients or

do research often involving complicated ethical issues, teachers continue to teach their students, and parliamentarians continue to debate the latest legislative initiatives.  But in every area those who know that we must ask whether what we are doing is good, are deeply distressed and those who believe goodness to be a question of purely personal "values" confirm the criticisms of the first group.  Confusion reigns at the highest levels but

daily life must and does go on and it may be years before the gnawing void at the centre of things leads to a visible collapse.  At  least that is so, for now, here in Canada.  It is not so elsewhere.</P>



<P>At other times, as today in other places, what were once "civilized"

cultures, not too dissimilar to ours, tear themselves apart, enslaving or eradicating

themselves and others in the process.  For the truth is that human beings have not

developed beyond the possibility of becoming bestial.  Compassion,

self-sacrifice and peaceful co-habitation, as aspects of a true humanity,

are willed states of being that are chosen by people on the basis of their

understanding of themselves and their beliefs.  But such choosing must be

informed and, until the erosion over recent centuries, information on the

precise nature of goodness was part of education and teaching about virtue

was seen as necessary preparation for a virtuous life and virtue was

understood as related to happiness.</P>



<P>Here in Canada, the increasing lack of teaching about morality and virtue in our education systems at all levels and its blossoming in every facet of life, is masked in the midst of a

more-or-less cohesive society.  But such chaos of thought is only hidden

and remains there like an undetected tumor, growing and active, but

ultimately, destructive.  Such an uneasy cultural peace must be replaced by

a deep and lasting peace based on people being taught what goodness is

grounded upon and subsists in.  What makes for coherence is that we share

in,and pursue, things that are good.  But the very idea of goodness is

disappearing because it is first doubted, then ignored.  Once what is good

is no longer taught, it becomes, on one level, forgotten, but because

goodness is a reality, its many faces continue to appear in our lives,

puzzling, reminding and tantalizing.</P>



<P>A related issue to this is that the centuries have seen a more-or-less

unbridled development of technology at a time when

education about purpose and the relationship between disciplines has been

in steadily decline.  As we have become increasingly adept at development,

we have become increasingly unable to apply technology in ways that are

non-destructive.  What comes heralded as bringing new joy and hope can soon

come to destroy and alienate.  Thus, introduction of a "labour saving

device" can result in reducing the number of labourers, destroying

community and family life, harming the environment and increasing the pace

of production and human life to an insupportable and unhealthy level.  Though labour may have been saved at the outset, leisure and the quality of life in the fullest sense have

decreased despite all the undoubted technological advancement.  We would be

wise to listen to the older people amongst us, who frequently speak about

the decrease in the quality of life they see around them.  When the ability

to do a thing technologically does not call for a deep analysis of whether

and how it should be done, we risk allowing technique to eradicate or deform purpose.</P>



<P>At this time it is clear that there is a need for fundamental reevaluation

of presuppositions.  This must be done by realizing what has gone wrong.

Then we can articulate purposes and recognize that a focus on the means of

techniques is inefficient and dangerous.  So, no matter what the

discipline, there needs to be a rethinking of foundations.  It is this work

of integration and education that the Centre has been established to

encourage.  Part of the Centre's function will be, through its Research

Board, publications and the holding of conferences, to analyze current

errors and abandonments and to rediscover and represent what has been

unjustifiably ignored. By the provision of papers and educational materials and the holding of forums, the Centre will provide an opportunity to people in the divided worlds of their disciplines to work together to assist a society deeply alienated from its purposes.  When such

a separation occurs on the level of disciplines, it is not surprising that we see a similar alienation on the personal level.  When a person sees no purpose for his or her life, it is a purpose and not a technique that is needed to fill this void.  The Centre's work then has both a social and a deeply personal aspect.  We hope that you will be a part of this work of rediscovery and renewal and will help support the Centre in this critical task.  To start, the publications (discussion papers, a newsletter and, eventually, a peer-reviewed Journal), set up the Research Board and begin our work, we need your support.  Please give generously.<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A></P>



<H4>Iain T. Benson<BR>

Senior Research Fellow<BR>

Centre for Renewal in Public Policy<BR>

Ottawa<BR>

11.viii.1994</H4>


<A NAME=1><P><SUP>1</SUP> The Centre is a charitable foundation and can issue tax deductible receipts for donations.</P>
<CENTER>

