<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #4 (Volume 1, No. 1)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 1<BR>
Article #4</H1></CENTER>

<H2>Assisted Dying:</H2>


<P><I>Iain T. Benson</I>



<P>The Latimer Verdict and Oregon's "Assistance in Dying" Law

Recently the debate surrounding death by choice has heated up.  Everyone is

talking and writing about the sentencing of Robert Latimer for killing his

cerebral palsied daughter on their Saskatchewan family farm.  in Oregon,

pro-euthanasia forces are celebrating the first law of its type in the

world, a law that will allow doctors to prescribe drugs they know are to be

used to bring about the death of the patient rather than to relieve the

patient's pain.</P>



<P>When people can kill for what they think are good motives, when doctors can

prescribe death rather than the alleviation of pain, they we have moved to

another kind of society altogether.  The concern of those who do not want

to be kept alive too long by artificial means is legitimate.  We do have to

learn that death is a natural part of life and modern medicine has been so

captivated by technology that it has sometimes lost sight of this fact.

Those who are afraid of dying in extreme pain need not have that fear as

any good palliative physician could tell them.  The fear of pain and of

being kept alive for too long are the fears that are being played upon by

the pro-euthanasia forces.  They (with the help of their friends in the

media) are manipulating the public.</P>



<P>In 1994 a Select Committee of the House of Lords, after an exhaustive

review, issued a Report<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A> which set out why they chose not to change their

laws to allow euthanasia or assisted-suicide.  The Committee's Report

stated that ". . . we do not think it possible to set secure limits on

voluntary euthanasia".  The members of this Committee, who rigorously

examined the Netherlands system, found that "it would be next to impossible

to ensure that all acts of euthanasia were truly voluntary, and that any

liberalization of the law was not abused", moreover, " . . . vulnerable

people - the elderly, lonely, sick or distressed - would feel pressure, whether real or imagined, to request

early death".  Even Derek Humphry of the Hemlock Society has admitted that

he knows that mistakes will occur in the working out of the Oregon

legislation.</P>



<P>In light of the emotional appeal of the Latimer case, and Oregon's recent

(and we hope, temporary) flirtation with the fringes of assisted suicide,

the conclusion of the Lords' Committee should be heard more widely across

North America:</P>



<P><I>"Ultimately however, we do not believe that these (pro-euthanasia and

assisted suicide) arguments are sufficient reason to weaken society's

prohibition of intentional killing.  That prohibition is the cornerstone of

law and of social relationships.  It protects each one of us impartially,

embodying the belief that all are equal.  We do not with that protection to

be diminished and we therefore recommend that there should be no change in

the law to permit euthanasia.  We acknowledge that there are individual

cases in which euthanasia may be seen by some to be appropriate.  But

individual cases cannot reasonably establish the foundation of a policy

which would have such serious and widespread repercussions.  Moreover,

dying is not only a personal or individual affair.  The death of a person

affects the lives of others, often in ways and to an extent which cannot be

foreseen.  We believe that the issue of euthanasia is one in which the

interest of the individual cannot be separated from the interest of society

as a whole."</I>  <A HREF="#2"><SUP>2</SUP></A></P>



<P>The jury came to the right conclusion in the Latimer case.  If there are

any lessons to be learned from that case they are in relation to why the

support for the family was not there or why the Latimer's chose not to

avail themselves of it (the way Sue Rodrigues refused to use the palliative

care that was offered to her).  If the law needs changing, it would be only

to provide greater flexibility in sentencing for second degree murder.  It

must not be as some suggest, a "third degree" murder charge).  For as the

Netherlands experience has shown, open that door of "mercy killing"

(Latimer) or "assistance in dying" (Oregon) and virtually anything can pass

through it no matter how carefully any "safeguards" are framed.  The hard

cases are always used to manipulate soft thought and it is for this reason

that it is said that "hard cases make bad law".</P>



<A NAME=1><P><SUP>1</SUP> House of Lords, Report of the Select Committee on Medical Ethics,

(London; HMSO), 1994</P>



<A NAME=2><P><SUP>2</SUP> ibid., p. 48 para 237, emphasis added.</P>



