<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #2 (Volume 1, No. 2)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 2<BR>
Article #2</H1></CENTER>

<H2>Why the Centre is not "RIGHT" or "LEFT"</H2>

<P><I>Iain T. Benson</I></P>

<P>Someone phoned recently worried that the Centre would be "pigeon-holed" if

it expressed certain opinions.  When asked how, the caller said, "Oh, you

know, as another right-wing Christian group".  The assumption seemed to be

that any group seeking to inform policy discussions with the riches of the

Jewish and Christian traditions would necessarily be "right wing".  The

words "Christian" and "right wing" seem to be found conveniently close to

one another in many articles in current journals and daily newspapers.

Perhaps the oft-mentioned "religious right" of the United States is the

boogey-person that looms in such people's imagination.  Without getting too

far into whether there is any useful meaning to the terms "left" and

"right" today, it is timely to reflect on the danger posed to analysis by

pigeon-holing.  Such pigeon-holing stands in for analysis more often than

not.  Many journalists seem unable to deal at all with an issue until they

can classify those who made the statements (on gender, class, race or

religious grounds) rather than deal with the statements  themselves.</P>



<P>The Centre's approach will be predictable in only one way:  it will be

sympathetic to the Judaeo-Christian    tradition which has been the matrix

of Western civilization.  All the Centre's members have a commitment to

this  tradition and believe that it is relevant to contemporary discussion

at every level.  The Centre will on occasion express a view that some would

consider "right wing", just as, from time to time it will express what some

would consider a "left wing" view.   The Centre might issue position

papers, but more often we will issue discussion papers, or host forums and

so forth.  Individual members of the Centre will speak their own minds in

ways that should foster deeper analysis than usual.<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A>   Our members will

speak about the importance of the Judaeo-Christian positions, as they

understand them, in connection with their own area(s) of expertise.  So

far, debates (and those who cover them here) allow little room for this

perspective.</P>



<P>The real problems with the "right" or "left" classification, and the

tendency to assume that religion means "right", are superficiality and

inaccuracy.  It is enough to say of someone that "Of course, she is, you

know, an N.D.P.'er" as if that is sufficient to describe her in all or even

in relevant respects.  Note how, in this example, the woman herself

disappears into whatever is meant by an "N.D.P.'er" regardless of the

position she holds on a particular issue.  So, too, with assuming that

Christian means "right wing".  This "party politics" way of looking at the

world is not the most fruitful way to deal with either people or issues.</P>



<P>At the moment Canadian society is knee-deep in superficial stereotyping.

Gender, race, political party, socio-economic class, all are used as an

excuse to label and, therefore, to dismiss the position put forward.</P>



<P>The Centre for Renewal in Public Policy will embody the principle of

"issue by issue" analysis.  Even if those involved in the Centre were to

support a particular party (which they do not), the Centre would not

endorse particular political parties.  That is not our role.  Our analysis

will be of issues rather than people and of principles rather than

parties.   If this rule were put into  practice by Canadian politicians and

journalists, they would command greater respect than they currently do.</P>



<P>All of us, including the journalists and politicians themselves, need to

foster deeper analysis and more meaningful dialogue.  We hope that by

linking disciplines and focusing on purposes as well as techniques,

the Centre will be of assistance in this effort.  There is no "quick fix"

for the serious problems that face Western democracies today, but we hope

that over time the quality of discussion will improve.   We look forward to

your comments with respect to anything the Centre produces.</P>



<H4>Iain Benson is the Centre's Senior Research Fellow and senior editor of the

Centre's publications.  He would like to thank Dr. Paul Nathanson of

Montreal for his editrorial assistance on both of his articles in this

issue.<BR></H4>



<A NAME=1><P><SUP>1</SUP>  Determining what the relevant questions are, and how best to pose them,

would itself be an important contribution to public policy formulation.  Failure to ask relevant questions ensures subsequent errors.</P>

