<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #1 (Volume 1, No. 2)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 2<BR>
Article #1</H1></CENTER>

<H2>The meaning of "RENEWAL"</H2>

<P>On several occasions, those speaking on behalf of the Centre have been

asked about the meaning of the word "renewal" in our title.  Of the various

definitions of "renewal," perhaps the one that best describes what we mean

is this: "to revive, reawaken, resuscitate" and "to bring back into use or

existence."  For the truth is, our society has ignored or forgotten some

things that are essential to our common life.  The term is used in a

positive way, therefore, to signify both hope and expectation.  The hope is

that our current cultural and public-policy situation is not beyond change

or improvement; the expectation is that with conviction, effort, and wide

spread support, our efforts will play a part in assisting such improvement.</P>



<P>What needs to be renewed?  For many years now, there has been, at every

level of society, a growing gap between the techniques of disciplines and

the purposes of  disciplines.  We have been learning how to do particular

things, in other words, but not what they are for.   This separation has

occurred in every area, whether it is law, medicine, politics, or education

itself.  We have stopped asking the big questions: in law, what do we mean

by justice and the common good?;  in education, what is the purpose and

moral content of education?; in medicine, what is the meaning of "health";

and, in politics, which matters are appropriate for government

intervention, and which  are  not?  All the while, the  technical focus of

each  discipline  has continued.  The vacuum becomes noticeable in any area

when a fundamental articulation is required in order to deal with an issue.</P>



<P>For example, to take an important question in the political realm, how

should parliamentarians deal with their public offices in relation to their

private beliefs?   In the legal area, what is the relation between law and

morals when it has to be decided whether a Criminal Code definition of

"obscenity" is challenged in light of the Charter's guaranteed "freedom of

expression"?   The way these questions are being handled at the highest

levels of Canadian society is an indication that something of grave

significance has already gone wrong<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A>.</P>



<P>Canadian public policy necessarily reflects the insight of its framers -

or their lack of it.  Indications are that major institutions are finding

it increasingly difficult to articulate their purposes or on what their

"ought" propositions are based.  Thus, we are treated to the spectacle of a

Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies rejecting the views of

most Canadians in favour of "Charter values" with respect to one issue<A HREF="#2"><SUP>2</SUP></A>,

but the Supreme Court of Canada interpreting the Charter according to the

wishes of the community by accepting a "community standards" test as a

valid way to determine what should be considered obscene on another<A HREF="#3"><SUP>3</SUP></A>.</P>



<P>Where "Charter values" are used in diametrically opposite ways, the

Charter can be used to justify virtually any outcome.  The Charter of

Rights cannot long be maintained as a meaningful document in a society that

no longer knows what is fundamental and for what reasons.  Attempts to

maintain the form of democracy without its substance (which includes, among

other things, representation and accountability) are doomed to fail over

time.</P>



<P>The rise of a functional chaos<A HREF="#4"><SUP>4</SUP></A> was predictable given that, for some time,

the prevailing system of schooling has not prepared us to deal with the

problems that face us as a country.  As a result, political debates have an

air of unreality about them, and laws are increasingly seen as emanating

from the politics of power rather than from any coherent understanding of

the person or the common good.  The Charter of Rights refers to

"fundamental rights and freedoms".  But what does "fundamental" mean?   It

is not surprising, therefore, that decisions are increasingly incoherent.</P>



<P>These fundamental rights and freedoms were not created yesterday.  They

emerged in a tradition. Its particular vision of human beings depends on

certain theological and philosophical notions that are not less valid

because they are now, in a sense, less "visible".  As C.S.Lewis once put it

on the first page of The Allegory of Love:</P>



<P><I>Humanity does not pass through phases as a train passes through stations:

being alive, it has the privilege of always moving yet never leaving anything behind.  Whatever we have been, in some sort we are still.</I></P>



<P>The current intellectual vacuum does not augur well for Canada's future.

Many  are   already concerned that key concepts (such as virtue and what a

developed character consists of)  have  to  be relearned (re-membered) so

that they can be promoted through public education.  Pluralism and nihilism

are not the same thing, and it is important to give meaning to the term

"pluralism" if nihilism is not to be the outcome of our current "value

neutral" endeavor.<A HREF="#5"><SUP>5</SUP></A></P>



<P>The Centre is pledged to assist in the work of re-articulation and renewal

for current and future needs.  We    cannot afford to be "chronological

snobs" who think today is necessarily better than yesterday.  Our task is

now, as it always ought to have been, to keep alive and to cherish those

truths that are essential to the maintenance and enjoyment of a flourishing

culture.  Those truths that the Charter speaks of as "fundamental" are part

of this culture.   How can we complain about the way people act when we

have ceased to teach them anything about morality?</P>



<P>It is not surprising that many highly schooled (but not morally educated)

members of the elite want to shy away from discussing morality.  This

highlights the seriousness of our current situation.  In Our Criminal Law

(1976) the Law Reform Commission of Canada pointed out that criminal law is

"fundamentally a moral system...a system of applied morality" (at p. 16).

Ultimately, our duty to obey the law itself is grounded, in part, on our

recognition of the moral duty to do so.  It is sobering to consider this

fact in light of contemporary crime statistics (see Gertrude Himmelfarb's

The De-moralization of Society [New York: Knopf, 1995]).<A HREF="#6"><SUP>6</SUP></A>  The Centre is

in the process of preparing Canadian statistics to see whether Himmelfarb's

graphic analysis is paralleled in Canada; we will be surprised if it

is not.  Ageless truths need to be cherished and transmitted by each

generation.  If that truth is lost, then it must be rediscovered and

renewed.<BR></P>



<H4>Iain Benson is the Centre's Senior Research Fellow<BR>

and senior editor of the Centre's publications.</H4>



<A NAME=1><P><SUP>1</SUP> Future articles will illustrate the lack of foundational coherence in

various areas including law and medicine.</P>



<A NAME=2><P><SUP>2</SUP> The Commission pointed out that most Canadians oppose donor insemination being available to lesbian couples but rejected this as relevant because of

"Charter values".  See: Proceed With Care, Report of The Royal

Commission on New Reproductive Technologies (Ottawa: Canadian

Communications Group, 1993): 456.</P>



<A NAME=3><P><SUP>3</SUP> R. v. Butler [1992] 2 W.W.R. 577 (S.C.C.).</P>



<A NAME=4><P><SUP>4</SUP> Functional chaos will follow theoretical chaos but how closely in each

area of society and how serious the outcomes, remain to be seen.  Having

identified the theoretical problems, however, it would seem foolish to wait

for further examples of its practical effects before making adjustments to

current approaches.</P>



<A NAME=5><P><SUP>5</SUP> There is, of course, no such thing as "value neutral."  That term, like

"pluralism", will be discussed and probed in future publications from the

Centre.</P>



<A NAME=6><P><SUP>6</SUP>   Himmelfarb's book is available for purchase through the Centre for

$34.00.  See enclosed order form.  Tables showing the Canadian statistical

data to parallel the tables found in this book are in preparation and will

be available this fall.</P>

