<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, March 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #3 (Volume 1, No. 1)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4><H1>Volume 1, No. 1<BR>
Article #3</H1></CENTER>

<H2>Reflections on the Media</H2>


<P><I>Phil Marchand</I>


<P>The media, both print and electronic, needs to be recognized for the

visceral art form that it is, and at best encountered with extreme prudence

by those who wish to be deeply informed as opposed to (or as well as)

entertained.</P>



<P>T.SE. Eliot once said he never read newspapers because they were too

exciting.  He was not being ironic, or referring merely to racy tabloids.

He was noticing a reality which most of us are too jaded or numb, by now,

to appreciate.  Newspapers of their nature - even the more sober variety,

such as the New York Times - intend to arouse, or excite, their readers.

Every editorial decision - involving lay-out, choice of art, phrasing of headlines and

captions, and of course, the editing and writing of articles, especially in

regard to lead paragraphs - in calculated to further that aim.</P>



<P>There is no use in expressing moral indignation at this state of affairs,

or bemoaning the "sensationalistic" or "superficial" press.  The electronic

media is, of course, even more attuned to the visceral and the shocking,

and adept at grabbing viewers' attention while numbing their rational

faculties.  Neither newspapers nor television and radio has much place for

sustained, reasoned argument.  This is not to say that newspapers don't run

good op-ed pieces on occasion, or convey useful information, but

institutions or groups with an interest in taking advantage of the media to

convey their views had better start with this reality in mind.</P>



<P>The media loves drama, and, of course, the essence of drama is conflict.

If there is an easily identifiable hero and villain involved in the

conflict, so much the better.  Failing that, any startling action or

statement - particularly pratfalls and gaffes on the part of the eminent - is meat and

drink to the media, both print and electronic.</P>



<P>Individuals and groups often complain that the media focus on such matters

at the expense of "substantive" issues.  We are made to feel guilty, for

example, about our media-induced fascination with O.J. Simpson.  An

argument can be made, however, that our guilty fascination - well

understood by the media - are an essential part of our

common humanity.  The O.J. Simpson story, after all, is about passion and

justice.  Why should we not be interested in it?  Personally, I would much

rather read accounts of O.J. Simpson's trial than all the political

commentary that's bound to precede the Quebec referendum.</P>



<P>Moreover, print reporters at their best, like good novelists, have an eye

for the telling detail that reveals more about a person or event than

official statements and press releases.  The off the cuff remarks, dress,

and casual behaviour of a politician, for example, might be considered

irrelevant by many people, but certainly not by Dickens or Flaubert.  They would see such

things as vital clues to character - and most readers, whether they thought about it

or not, would  agree.</P>



<P>Certainly it is frustrating for individuals and groups who have a message

to convey to find that message thwarted by the reporting of the media.  I

don't think the Writers' Union of Canada, for example, is too pleased with

my reporting of its annual meetings.  Doubtless, the union would rather

have its highly important resolutions on funding of the arts publicized,

but I have tended to focus on nasty shouting matches over issues such as

racial minority writers' conferences - partly because I believe such

unpleasant incidents truly are more significant than the union's

resolutions.  They illuminate the kind of issues that actually move people.</P>



<P>The political bias of the reporter has less to do with these matters than

is generally realized.  I recall a feminist conference that took place in Alberta some

years ago, in which an invited speaker, Andrea Dworkin, made some

outrageous comments about women taking vigilante action against rapists, or

some such offenders.  In most reports, those remarks were headlined.</P>



<P>Moreover, a woman reporter for the Edmonton Journal, I believe, ignored the

remarks or placed them near the bottom of her story.  When questions as to

her judgement in so doing, she replied that she felt the work of the conference

was the real story.  It was "important."  In other words, she completely

bought the agenda of the conference organizers.  If she had been

covering a conference of Progressive Conservatives, or Reform Party

delegates, or some other group she detested, and someone made a racist

joke, guess what would have been featured in her lead paragraph?</P>



<P>This incident is notable, however, because it is uncommon.  Most reporters

know what their editors and readers find interesting, and that's what they

report, even if they don't like it.</P>



<P>Given this reality, those having to deal with the media should think of it

as an art form, not a bulletin board or loudspeaker or conveyor belt for

messages.  Like all art forms it deals not in intellectual propositions but

in impressions calculated to produce an effect on an audience.  If a group

wants to exploit this art form, it had better think very carefully about

such impressions, and how they can be produced.  It had better think, in

short, like an artist - or an advertiser or a propagandist.  In short, people should

recognize what the media, as it is currently constituted, can and cannot

do.  If learned analysis is sought in the vast majority of cases groups

must look elsewhere than the popular media.</P>



<P>From a Christian perspective, however, it might well appear that all such

effort is wasted.  I have often reflected that individuals who find

themselves talking to reporters should remember a few simple rules, mostly

negative in character.  Never give your enemies free publicity is one such

rule, for example.  (If Archbishop Ambrozic had remembered this rule in an

interview he gave last year to Toronto Life magazine, in which he slammed a

left winged Catholic activist, he would have saved himself much grief.)

But these rules are a matter, largely, of common sense - trying to go

further in the matter media savvy, in an attempt to manipulate the media,

is probably a fool's game.</P>



<P>Ultimately nothing can take the place of rigorous thought and argument, which is

not what the media is looking for.  And of course no medium of communication ever conceived is as potent, on this unhappy earth, as prayer.<BR></P>



<H4>Phil Marchand is Books Columnist at the Toronto Star.<BR>

He is the author of an award winning biography of Marshall McLuhan<BR>

and his first crime novel, Deadly Spirits was published by Stoddart Publishing of Toronto in 1994.</H4>

