<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, May 1996, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #2 (Volume 1, No. 3)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4>
<H1>Volume 1, No. 3<BR>Article #2</H1></CENTER>

<H2>Religious Morality and Public Policy</H2>

<P><I>John Redekop<BR>
Professor of Political Science (on leave), Wilfred Laurier University<BR>
Research Scholar in Residence, Trinity Western University</I></P>

<P>Was Reinhold Niebuhr correct when he asserted that "Democracy is that child
of which Christianity need never be ashamed"?  Given centuries of
intolerance and religious wars, often involving "Christian" societies, can
one really claim that not only are Christianity
and democracy compatible, but that Christianity actually promotes the
democratic tradition?</P>

<P>The major religions of the world were all enunciated initially as creeds
by which people should live.  Moses, the prophet Mohammed, and Jesus Christ
- to name three enunciators - all spelled out moral codes intended to
restrain evil, to reward goodness, to facilitate distinguishing between the
two, and to encourage that which is good.  For centuries various countries
have sought to establish legal codes which incorporated these religious
moral codes.  Often, in their crusading and ideological zeal, true
believers set aside toleration and free choice and ended up with brutal
realities such as the Spanish inquisition, the Cromwellian dictatorship, or
the Islamic persecution of religious dissidents as in modern Iran and
Pakistan.</P>

<P>The question to be investigated in this essay is whether the
Judeo-Christian ethic, the behavioural component of these two faith-based
world views, is not only a pragmatically desirable ethic for adherents to
follow but can also serve as a very useful guideline in the formation of
public policy in a religiously plural society such as Canada (even though
the two faiths espouse different creeds, they have sufficiently common
ethic to allow us to speak of a single hyphenated entity).  Whether other
faiths could also serve as an ethical foundation for a religiously plural
democracy deserves analysis in its own right.</P>

<P>In the Canadian case, of course, well over 80 percent of the population
identifies with the Judeo-Christian world view and thus most Canadians have
a predisposition to accept the ethic as generally valid.  But this fact
does not, in itself, provide any justification for having public policy
shaped by Judeo-Christian principles.  For that we must evaluate the
overall utility of the Judeo-Christian ethic in developing a set of public
policies which will advance the good of all, while simultaneously sustaining
and promoting the democratic political system itself.</P>

<P>In seeking to ascertain whether the central principles of the
Judeo-Christian ethic provide the kind of soil in which the democratic
tradition will thrive, what arguments and evidence should we consider?  How
can we find out whether this world-view really can advance the social and
political well-being of all religious groups, and all non-believers, in
Canada, or elsewhere for that matter?  Let us spell out and assess four
fundamental assertions which lie at the heart of the Judeo-Christian
faiths.</P>

<P>First, these faiths strongly emphasize the worth and dignity of every
individual.  Every person is seen as being made in the image of God and
therefore possessing a spark of the divine.  Human beings, in this
perspective, are not seen as the highest form of animal evolution but as
the only creature which God made in his own image.</P>

<P>We encounter here the startling assertion that every individual,
possessing a God-breathed eternal soul, is worth more than the whole world.
Such an affirmation makes a person much more than a producer, a consumer,
a voter, a resident, a taxpayer, a party member, or a citizen with a S.I.N.
It imbues every individual, whether Judeo-Christian or not, with great
potential, profound worth, and eternal significance.  It comes as no
surprise then,
to discover that, generally speaking, states in Christendom have gone to
great lengths to guard the dignity and freedom of all people, to respect
their views, and to facilitate the development and
political participation of every person in the realm.</P>

<P>Second, the Judeo-Christian faiths stress the equal worth of all human
beings, from the youngest to the oldest, from all races, from all classes
and from both sexes.  This emphasis on equal worth, rooted in God's
commandments, reinforces the crucial democratic suppositions concerning
equality before the law, equality in voting power, and equality as objects
of government policy.</P>

<P>Third, the basic emphasis in these two faiths which holds that the
faithful are their "brother's keeper" generates both a social consciousness
and a sense of obligation concerning human rights.  The resulting social
consciousness goes a long way in explaining why Judeo-Christian societies
led the world in the provision of assistance to the poor, the ill, the
elderly, and the disadvantaged generally.  It probably also explains, in
part, why these same societies led the world in the pioneering of foreign
aid.  Such material aid, after all, becomes part of the God-decreed,
inclusive "missionary mandate".</P>

<P>Fourth, and most significant, we find in the Jewish and Christian faiths a
central assertion of voluntarism.  While Jews and Christians promote the
importance of discovering "God's truth", they also acknowledge the constant
option of rejecting "God's truth".  God has willed it thus.  Therein lies
the basis of freedom, of human choice and human responsibility.  In other
words, because of the requirement of voluntarism, the Jewish and Christian
faiths cannot be coerced.  Indeed, according to the Holy Scriptures of both
faiths, "coerced faith" constitutes a contradiction in terms.  External
behaviour can be coerced; internal beliefs cannot be coerced.  While some
misguided zealots, down through the ages, have attempted to force Christian
conversion, the religion itself, as also the Jewish faith, allows no place
for such activity.  These faiths recognize only a personal and voluntary
response, be it positive or negative, to God's message.</P>

<P>The vitally important political consequence of this emphasis on
voluntarism and choice can hardly be overstated.  It consists of a
commitment to fundamental freedom for all - for Jews, for Christians, for
believers in other faiths, and for those without belief in any faith.  For
theological reasons, Jews and Christians, when true to their creeds, grant
full religious freedom to all groups.</P>

<P>But the granting of this freedom, indeed, the insistence on it, also means
that Jews and Christians, when acting consistently, strongly support the
related freedoms - speech, assembly, privacy, political involvement, etc. -
without which religious freedom cannot exist.  Thus the logic of the
Judeo-Christian ethic, rooted in the central teaching of the faiths,
extends multifaceted freedom to all groups and does so up to the point at
which people seriously harm themselves, deny similar freedom to others, or
seek to destroy the very system which spells out and guarantees these basic
rights for all.</P>

<P>Thus it happens that the Judeo-Christian ethic insists on rights for
majorities as well as minorities and for groups as well as individuals.
When disputes occur, neither side shall be permitted to manipulate or suppress
the other.  Such an insistence on reasonable limits and restraints, applied
equally to all, does not weaken the basic commitment to freedom for all.
As Thomas Hobbes explained, more than three centuries ago, anarchy does not
constitute freedom.

<P>An insistence on freedom of religion for all does not, however, mean
insistence on the equality of all religions.  The mutually contradictory
claims of various faiths makes such an assertion illogical.  After all,  if
one faith asserts that Jesus was the Son of God and the other says that he
was not, they cannot both be true.  The resulting challenge for public
policy makers, at every governmental level, who hold to the Judeo-Christian
ethic, is to promote full freedom of religion and the acceptance of
religious pluralism while simultaneously, in the private and fully
voluntary sectors of their lives, affirming the uniqueness and presumed
superiority of the faith which they possess.  Such personal or
congregational faith nurturing and faith proclamation are done outside of
the arena of public policy, and without any specific assistance from the
arm of the law.</P>

<P>Unfortunately, throughout history we find examples of policy-makers who
claimed adherence to the Judeo-Christian ethic but did not hold to these
theologically-rooted principles.  They ignored, in political practice, the
perspective they generally continued to stress in their theological
statements, namely, that Jews and Christians uphold freedom because God
posits respect for free choice as central in his dealings with all
humankind.  When believers in the Judeo-Christian faiths neglect this
emphasis on free choice, they often become arrogant, intolerant, and even
vindictive.</P>

<P>The point warrants reinforcement, especially as it relates to
policy-makers.  Difficult as it may be, consistent believers in Judaism and
Christianity, even as they assert their own religious beliefs,
simultaneously insist on public policies which affirm toleration and which
grant full freedom for all other faith groups.  Moral choice is what God
gives them; moral choice is what they insist on for themselves and others.</P>

<P>Given the above, it seems reasonable to state that non-Christians can with
good conscience and integrity, accept and affirm the Judeo-Christian ethic
for its general utility - it serves them well.  Thus for example, the
Shiites, Sunnis and other Islamic groups would readily acknowledge that
they presently enjoy far greater religious and other freedoms in western
democracies such as Canada, the United States and the United Kingdom, all
part of Christendom, than they enjoy in Iran and several other countries
which are part of the Muslim world.</P>

<P>It is also important to underscore the fact that public ethos and a
dominant faith are not synonymous.  Therefore, the Judeo-Christian ethic
can be dominant in a religiously plural society and can, for good reasons,
be supported by non-Judeo-Christian groups, without constituting any threat
to the free activity of minority faith groups.  Indeed, one could even
argue that the success of minority faiths would, in fact, be enhanced if
supporters of those faiths also supported public adherence to the
Judeo-Christian ethos with its insistence on freedom for all.</P>

<P>For Jews and Christians, the public policy challenge is two-fold.  These
believers, in public office and elsewhere, must promote freedom for all and
affirm the propriety of religious diversity.  Simultaneously, they must
strengthen their own faith communities and even seek to enlarge them, so
that the generally beneficial Judeo-Christian ethos will not be weakened or
lost.  In sum, Jews and Christians live out their faith, proclaim their
faith, and nurture their faith so that all people in society will benefit.</P>

<P>The legal scholar, John Warwick Montgomery, for years the Director of the
International Institute of Human Rights Summer School in Strasbourg,
France, has made some startling assertions.  In public lectures and in his
writings he has said that only Christianity can make a stand on human
rights that is more than an extension of a particular prejudice.  Outside
of the Judeo-Christian ethic it is difficult to find a catalogue of rights
which human beings should uphold on behalf of each other.  In this
connection we do well to remember that international human rights documents
such as the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, proclaimed by the
General Assembly of the United Nations in 1948, were built on this ethic.</P>

<P>This academic, with eight earned degrees, author of more than one hundred
articles and of Human Rights and Human Dignity  and History and
Christianity, has written that a Christian "will ...condemn without
partiality violations of human rights whenever they occur and without
regard to the politics of the violators;  and he will strive to promote and
protect the dignity of every man without fear or favor." <A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A></P>

<P>Given our review of the Judeo-Christian ethic, can we concur with
Montgomery's assertion?  Can we further concur with the notion that careful
adherence to the authentic Judeo-Christian ethic, and protection of its key
principles, constitutes a sound guideline for decision-makers entrusted
with the development and enactment of public policy in our times?<BR></P>

<P><A NAME=1><SUP>1</SUP></A>  From Montgomery, John, Human Rights and Human Dignity (1979), as quoted
in Kitchener-Waterloo Record, November 21, 1987, p.E9.</P>

