<HTML><HEAD><!-- Produced by Rohm Communications, <<Enter DATE Here>>, Tel: (613) 825-9968, E-mail: rohm@iosphere.net -->
<TITLE>CRPP - Centrepoints Article #3 (Volume 1, No. 3)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<a href="http://www.rohmcom.com/bin/imagemap.cgi/crppnews">
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="./gifs/news.jpg" ALT="Menu Bar" BORDER=0 ISMAP="ISMAP"></CENTER>
</a>

<CENTER><HR SIZE=4><IMG SRC="./gifs/cplogo.gif" ALT="Centrepoints" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=38><HR SIZE=4>
<H1>Volume 1, No. 3<BR>Article #3</H1></CENTER>

<H2>In Memoriam of George Rawlyk<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>Christian Historian, Head, Dept. of History, Queen's Univ.<BR>
Member of the Centre's Advisory Council</FONT></H2>

<P>George Rawlyk was Canada's leading scholar of evangelicalism and Canada's
leading Christian historian.  His death on November 23, 1995, from
complications following a car accident, tears a huge hole in the scholarly
and Christian community.  Born in 1935, he was raised in an immigrant home
in Thorold, Ontario.  The decisive moment in his life came in his
conversion to Christ in a Baptist Sunday School.  That fired his
path-breaking scholarship, his radical politics, his loyal church
allegiance and his profound care for, and encouragement to, generations of
graduate students and colleagues.</P>

<P>Rawlyk was best known to many Canadians for his major role in the 1993
"God is Alive!" special issue of Maclean's.  The largest-ever survey of
Canadian religious attitudes produced some strikingly unexpected results,
showing that a far larger proportion of the population holds strongly
Christian beliefs, even though church-going has dropped off steeply since
the 1960s.  This suggested to Rawlyk that much so-called secularization in
Canada affected government institutions and the cultural elite much more
than it did the "Canadian grass roots."<A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A> Rawlyk had planned to follow
this research with a comparative Canadian-American survey between now and
2000.</P>

<P>A large, rough-hewn, athletic man who almost always wore running shoes,
Rawlyk's career started with a choice between pro-football (he played
centre on a McMaster University team with Russ Jackson as quarterback) and
a Rhodes scholarship to Oxford.  He chose the latter, and while at Oxford,
became president of the Oxford Inter-Collegiate Christian Union.  He
subsequently taught at Queen's University for nearly thirty years.  He was
head of the Department of History from 1976-1985.  He chose to work in
relatively neglected and unpopular fields to demonstrate successfully their
central significance for understanding Canada's past and present.</P>

<P>This meant exploring the his-tory of the Atlantic provinces - he received
an honorary Doctor of Civil Laws degree from Acadia University in October,
1995 - and the history of Christianity in Canada.  In May, 1995, a
first-ever conference held at Queen's on "Aspects of the Canadian
Evangelical Experience" drew scholars from across the country - many of
whom had been his graduate students - and around the world.  McGill-Queen's
Press, for which Rawlyk edited the series "Studies in the History of
Religion," will publish the book of conference papers in 1996.</P>

<P>Increasingly, Rawlyk had ex-plored not just religious groups and events
but also their influence on broader historical movements.  He insisted on
taking seriously the words and actions of participants, especially
ordinary, everyday people, rather than subjecting them to "superior"
academic scrutiny or casting doubt on their sincerity or seriousness.  But
he also traced the lines of their later impact.  He was fascinated, for
instance, with the apparent capacity of Canadian Christians to accommodate
others who differ from them on doctrinal or political grounds, in contrast
with the polarization on such matters that is often evident south of the
border.</P>

<P>Rawlyk was an exponent of what might be called "the new Christian
historiography" developed since the 1970s by historians such as Mark Noll,
Nathan Hatch and George Marsden in the USA and David Bebbington and David
Hempton in the UK [although this list is male, the second generation of
this group includes a number of distinguished women such as Edith Blumhofer
(USA) and Marguerite Van Die (the Canadian)].  Though he started his career
as a Christian, and spent many years studying religious history, it was not
until the 1980s that he came to the "fundamental change of perspective"<A HREF="#2"><SUP>2</SUP></A>
that made him question his previous approach.  Why not write one's story in
a Christian way?</P>

<P>Rawlyk recognized that how-ever hard one tries to be honest in using
evidence, fair to different interpretation and consistent in one's
conclusions, intellectual work is never neutral.  It is done for particular
purposes and is influenced consciously or unconsciously by assumptions made
by the author.</P>

<P>He never pretended that by doing history Christianly one could thus discern
what is "properly Christian."  But he did believe that forming judgments
and theories of change from a Christian perspective was part of a properly
Christian practice, and one that should be publicly accessible to believer
and unbeliever alike.</P>

<P>Rawlyk will also be remembered for his loyal-but-critical attachments to
First Baptist Church in Kingston, to the New Democratic Party - he once
campaigned with the NDP leader Ed Broadbent - and to Queen's University.
Needless to say, Rawlyk was sometimes involved in controversy.  While he
held his ground tenaciously, he could also see another person's
perspective, as well as their debating points, and, over time, modify his
views.</P>

<P>At Queen's, students, above all, nurture fond memories of him.  He was
well-known for the open door to his office - although students also knew
not to bother him unless their visit had a purpose - and for the care and
concern shown to each person, especially if he or she were anxious, hard-up
or harassed.  He was known for his support of female professors in a
male-dominated academic environment.  As a colleague, I found him always as
interested in my family situation - he was himself married
with two grown daughters - as he was in my work.</P>

<P>As universities come under increasing pressure to rationalize and
restructure, the example of persons such as George Rawlyk will become
central as a beacon of hope.  To have the courage of one's convictions, to
passionately promote scholarship and social justice, to create communities
rather than pursue self-interest, to be genuinely concerned about daily
life realities of relationships and, in his case, to be a candidly
committed Christian, are traits seldom found in one person.  Simply, he was
the salt of the earth.<BR></P>

<H4>David Lyon is Professor and Head of the Sociology Department at Queen's
University, Kingston, Ontario.</H4>

<P><A NAME=1><SUP>1</SUP></A> The Canada Fire, Montreal and Kingston: McGill-Queen's University Press,
1994, p. 211.</P>

<P><A NAME=2><SUP>2</SUP></A>  Wrapped up in God, Burlington: Welch, 1988, p.152.</P>

