<HEAD>
<TITLE>"Tis the Season... for RRSP's!"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>

<A HREF="./jan_p1.html"> <B><H1>... Thinking Outside the Box</B>
<BR><I>Issue #1 - January 1996</I></H1></A>
<H2>P. B. FRASER & ASSOCIATES<BR>
Financial Strategies Group</H2>
<HR SIZE=4>
<H1><I>"Tis the Season... for RRSP's!"</I>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=left SIZE=8 NOSHADE></H1>
<H4>By Rob Redman, CMA</H4><BR>

<P>That's right, for all those of you who are guilty of procrastinating on your RRSP contributions, get moving now or lose out for 1995.  Since their introduction in 1957, RRSP's have become the single most
important vehicle for long term investing in Canada.  For the 1994 tax year over 5.3 million Canadians
contributed over $20.9 billion to their RRSP's.  Now over half of all Canadian households own at least one
RRSP.  These numbers are up substantially from even a few year ago, but how do you rate?</P>

<P>As much as we may take them for granted, RRSP's are most likely the best program available in any
country in the world for the "average person" to accumulate significant wealth.  If you think about it, we
really do have it pretty good.  We can make contributions to our own investment portfolios that are tax
deductible.  The portfolio is completely under our own control and we can even invest outside of our
country, and  yet the money still grows tax deferred.  Sure there are limits on how much we can put in,
and the withdrawal rules are a little cumbersome, but where else in the world could you find such a tax
advantaged way to save for your retirement?<IMG SRC="./gifs/hrglass.gif" WIDTH=194 HEIGHT=382 ALIGN=right></P>

<P>There was an interesting article  in the Financial Post in December that discussed a poll that Royal Trust had done regarding RRSP's.  Apparently about 49% of the poll respondents planned to put money into
RRSP's this year.  Of all those people who will make contributions, only 28% plan on using some foreign
content.  The average contribution this year will be $4,049, which doesn't look like much, but that's up
about 10% from last year, and the average RRSP account is worth $30,102.</P>

<P>Now you can rank yourself versus those figures, if you want to, but those don't tell the whole story.  In the same poll some shocking figures were revealed.  Given all of the positive numbers above, 24% of all
respondents still expect their standard of  living to fall in retirement.  19 % expect the Canada Pension
Plan to go bust by the time  they retire and 11% are concerned about ill health and the rising cost of
medical care.  If this is the case it would  seem only logical for people to avail themselves of some
financial expertise to help them meet their objectives.  Although this may be true, 68% of all respondents
have never met with a financial advisor and 41% have never made an RRSP contribution.</P>

<P>I guess the lesson is, to take care of yourself because nobody else will.  If you know someone who could
use our assistance in getting their plan underway, please feel free to  have them give us a call.  If you
care about them, you'll recommend them to a skilled group of professionals.  In terms of your own plans,
make sure you call us soon if you need to get in before February 29th. </P>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=65%>
