<HEAD>
<TITLE>Will your retirement plans become a reality?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>

<A HREF="./jan_p1.html"> <B><H1>... Thinking Outside the Box</B>
<BR><I>Issue #1 - January 1996</I></H1></A>
<H2>P. B. FRASER & ASSOCIATES<BR>
Financial Strategies Group</H2>
<HR SIZE=4>
<H1><I>Will your retirement plans become a reality?</I>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=left SIZE=8 NOSHADE></H1>
<H4>By Allan Weiss</H4><BR>

<P>You've been saving for retirement for years--putting money into your registered retirement savings plans, perhaps on a monthly basis, perhaps annually. On the other hand, if money has been in short supply,
you've been delaying, but "next year for sure" you'll make a contribution. What happens if you're disabled
before your retirement plan is built? If you're like most people who have employment or business income,
you may have some group or private disability benefits that will pay you. Unfortunately, such benefits will
in all likelihood be used entirely to meet ongoing living expenses and other needs, and your RSP contribution room, based as it is on "earned income", will be at best reduced. It's highly unlikely that you'll
have anything left to put away towards retirement.</P>

<P>There are solutions available. Either as a separate policy or as a rider to a more complete disability policy, you can obtain a guarantee that your retirement assets will grow as you planned:  an arrangement that will continue to accumulate an investment pool for you, in the event that you become disabled. The plan is flexible, permanent, non-cancellable, and guaranteed, and the cost is surprisingly affordable. Contact us for further details.</P>

<HR SIZE=4>

