<HEAD>
<TITLE>Capital Market Overview and Outlook 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>

<A HREF="./jan_p1.html"> <B><H1>... Thinking Outside the Box</B>
<BR><I>Issue #1 - January 1996</I></H1></A>
<H2>P. B. FRASER & ASSOCIATES<BR>
Financial Strategies Group</H2>
<HR SIZE=4>
<H1><I>Capital Market Overview and Outlook 1996</I>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=left SIZE=8 NOSHADE></H1>
<H4>By Chris Johnson</H4><BR>

<P>Looking at a general economic overview of Canada we can see some evidence that the fiscal restraints
being implemented by the federal and provincial governments are showing some positive effects on the
markets. Lower interest rates, a stronger Canadian dollar, a strong domestic stock market and low
inflation are all signs that our fiscal reform is being taken seriously.</P>

<P>Equity Markets: <BR>
1995 was a good year for the Canadian stock market. The performance we saw throughout the year
shows good quality growth based on fundamentals, increased corporate profits, low inflation and solid
commodity prices. These increases are not resulting in an "overheated" market. This will allow for another
good year in the Canadian stock markets offering opportunity for investors to find the returns they seek.</P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=6>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>Dec. 29, 1995</TD><TD>Dec. 30, 1994</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>TSE 300 Index</TD><TD>4,689.10</TD><TD>4,202.65</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>S & P 500 Index</TD><TD>614.12</TD><TD>461.16</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Prime Lending Rate</TD><TD>7.50%</TD><TD>8.00%</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Canadian Dollar (in U.S.$)</TD><TD>$0.7335</TD><TD>$0.7124</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>30 Year Cdn Bond Yield</TD><TD>7.589%</TD><TD>9.167%</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>One thing we must be cautious about is the US stock market. Differing opinions say anything from the
U.S. hitting dangerous levels, to a restructuring of the way business is being done resulting in the
strongest bull market in years. The Canadian market does follow the U.S. market and if the U.S. stays
out of trouble (and it should) , we will be in good shape for 1996. Continuing to buy quality companies and
holding them remains a sound strategy that should pay dividends this year.</P>

<P>Fixed Income Markets:<BR>
1996 will be different from 1995. We saw a spike in short term rates during the early part of 1995 that
created opportunity for professional managers to realize some great gains over the course of the year.
At the present level there is not much room for further declines in interest rates and it is suspected that
this will hold true for most of 1996. This means that one should not expect much more than the interest
on bonds over the next 12 months. It will be unlikely that there will be any growth from capital gains in
bonds and bond funds. As the referendum approached we saw an increase in the spread between
Canada and US interest rates as our political instability  made us more of a risk to investors. With the
resulting NO vote we have seen this spread shrink back to almost normal levels.</P>

<P>We advise investors in the fixed income markets to focus on short to medium term investments. This
takes away some of the risk should short term interest rates increase again. When investing be sure to
examine <B>all</B> your options and do not make a decision on what something <B>did</B> over the last 12 months.</P>

<HR SIZE=4>

