<HEAD>
<TITLE>Power of Attorney or Public Guardian and Trustee - Your Choice</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>

<A HREF="./jan_p1.html"> <B><H1>... Thinking Outside the Box</B>
<BR><I>Issue #1 - January 1996</I></H1></A>
<H2>P. B. FRASER & ASSOCIATES<BR>
Financial Strategies Group</H2>
<HR SIZE=4>
<H1><I>Power of Attorney or Public Guardian and Trustee - Your Choice</I>
<HR WIDTH=92% ALIGN=left SIZE=8 NOSHADE></H1>
<H4>By Mitchell Besner</H4><BR>

<P>Did you know that if you become incapacitated and have not executed a Continuing Power of Attorney,
you will have to rely on the Public Guardian and Trustee of Ontario to manage your pressing financial
affairs?  Your financial planner has very good reasons for advising you that a Power of Attorney is an
essential element of a comprehensive estate plan.</P>

<P>The goal of a Continuing Power of Attorney (the term "Continuing" refers to the fact that you want the
Power of Attorney to continue throughout the period that you are incapacitated) is to delegate the power
to make decisions on your behalf to someone of your choice, who will be called your attorney.  Your
attorney may be your spouse, a relative, trusted friend or trust company, or some combination of such
parties.  Either in your Continuing Power of Attorney or the letter of direction to your lawyer that should
accompany this document, you  will limit the circumstances under which your Continuing Power of
Attorney can be used; generally, to the loss of the ability to act for yourself, whether due to illness or
injury.</P>

<P>You also specify the types of decisions that you want your attorney to make on your behalf.  Matters of
personal care, such as the consent to medical treatment, are properly kept separate from those dealing
with your financial affairs.  You can cover these decisions in a document called a Power of Attorney for
Personal Care.  Perhaps a subsequent article can deal with this type of Power of Attorney.  Now I would
like to focus on the Power of attorney which governs your financial affairs, formally called the Continuing
Power of Attorney for Property.</P>

<P>Under the new law in Ontario, which came into effect on April 3,1995, if you become incapacitated and
do not have a valid Continuing Power of Attorney, the Public Guardian and Trustee of Ontario (the PGT)
will step in and take over the management of your financial affairs.  Your next of kin would then have to
apply to the PGT to replace it as what is called your Statutory Guardian of Property.  This application will
have to be supported by, amongst other things, a management plan and an undertaking to provide
security to the PGT.  As our population ages and the resources of the PGT become stretched beyond
their limitations, this procedure, in addition to being costly, could take months; in the interim an
over-burdened PGT would be responsible for managing your day-to-day financial affairs.</P>

<P>On the other hand, if you have a Continuing Power of Attorney, your attorney simply needs to obtain an
original or notarized copy of that document.  He or she will then be able to act on your behalf and do such
things as pay your bills, renew your mortgage and provide instructions to your financial planner.  The only
thing you cannot delegate to your attorney is the power to sign a new Last Will and Testament.</P>

<P>Only if you are certified as incapable of managing your property under the Mental Health Act will a
Continuing Power of Attorney not prevent the PGT from getting involved in your affairs.  But that is only
in the short term.  If you have a pre-existing Continuing Power of Attorney, the person named as attorney
would be in a much better position to take over the management of your affairs from the PGT than would
your next of kin if you did not have one.  For example, your appointed attorney would not have to submit
a management plan or prove to the PGT that he or she is a suitable replacement.  As well, the PGT would
be bound by law to approve  your attorney's application within thirty days from the date your attorney
submits his or her application, unless the PGT has reasonable grounds to believe that you were not
mentally capable at the time you signed the Continuing Power of Attorney.</P>

<P>Preparing a Continuing Power of Attorney for Property is an inexpensive way to ensure that if you are not able to care for yourself, your financial affairs will be handled expeditiously by the person or persons of
your choice.</P>

<P>Mitchell Besner is an Ottawa lawyer who practises as a sole practitioner.  He can be reached at 798-7858.</P>

<HR SIZE=4>

