<HEAD><TITLE>No Strings Attached Insurance?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4>

<A HREF="./jan_p1.html"> <B><H1>... Thinking Outside the Box</B>
<BR><I>Issue #1 - January 1996</I></H1></A>
<H2>P. B. FRASER & ASSOCIATES<BR>
Financial Strategies Group</H2>
<HR SIZE=4>
<H1><I>"No Strings Attached" Insurance?</I>
<HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=left SIZE=8 NOSHADE></H1>
<H4>By Allan Weiss.</H4><BR>

<P>No doubt you've all had your T.V. time interrupted, at one point or another, by advertisements from an insurance company which shall remain nameless (but  whose initials are N.U.), offering life insurance with no medical examination required.  At first glance, this may look like a great deal, but even on the basis of common sense alone, you know there has to be a catch somewhere.  Why would an insurance company
take on the risk of insuring someone whose medical history is a complete unknown?  Obviously, the venture must somehow be profitable.  As insurance is a field that is highly competitive, and likely to become more so in future, logic alone would suggest two conclusions:</P>

<P>1.  The amount of insurance  offered is relatively small, and,</P>
<P>2.  The premiums would be at the higher end of the price range.</P>

<P>This in fact turns out to be the reality of the situation.  But what if you have a major health condition that you think might make you uninsurable?  Should you rush to the phone?  Once again, there's really no free lunch;  if you die within two years of purchasing the policy, my reading of the situation is that your estate or beneficiary receives only 1.5 times the premiums you paid--not the full death benefit.</P>

<P>The obvious conclusion is this:  if you think you need insurance, get your advisor to get you one or more price quotations from good companies, and apply for a policy.  The application alone obligates you to
nothing whatsoever.  The chances are that you will be accepted for a policy, and the price may be less
than you think.  Even if you have a health problem, this does not often result in an outright refusal.  Usually,
you'll be "rated", meaning that you'll have to pay a higher premium, to compensate the insurance company
for the added risk they're incurring by accepting you as a client--but you'll still have your coverage.  If you
don't like the end result, you need not accept the policy, but at least you'll have the satisfaction of knowing
that you "did your homework", and in all likelihood you'll end up with a better policy than if you had simply
responded to a mass marketing ploy.</P>

<P>If you'd like to read more on this topic, I have in my possession an interesting article from a 1993 edition of the Financial Post.  Feel free to call me for a copy.</P>

<HR SIZE=4>

