<html>
<!--IT&E_WEAT.HTM-->
<head>
<title>
Talaya Weather Page
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/weatbar.gif">
</center>

<table border=0 width=605>
<td>
Local weather forecasting services are available from several local media sources.  The <STRONG>U. S. National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration</STRONG> (NOAA) island forecasts for Guam, Rota, Tinian and Saipan are broadcast by continuous radio transmission on Station WXM85 (162.40 mHz).  Recorded weather forecasts for Guam with coastal marine conditions are available by local telephone at 711, 477-2991 or 477-5992.
</td></TABLE><BR>
<table border=0 width=605>
<td><IMG SRC="images/nws1guam.gif"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-2>(photo courtesy of NOAA)</FONT><BR>
</td>
<td width=600>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>NOAA</STRONG> Guam Weather Service</FONT><BR>
The <A HREF="http://tgsv5.nws.noaa.gov/pr/guam/p1.htm" target="_parent">NOAA Home Page for Guam!</A> introduces the National Weather Service Office for our island.  Download a current <A HREF="http://www.nws.noaa.gov/pr/guam/nwsoguam.gif" target="_parent">satellite photo</A> of our local forecast area. 
</td>
</table>

<table border=0 width=605>
<td>
<IMG SRC="images/earthsu2.gif" width=160 BORDER=0><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-2>(photo courtesy of NOAA)</FONT>
</td><BR>
<td width=600>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>NOAA</STRONG> National Climatic Data Center</FONT>
<BR>
The National Climatic Data Center Home Page gives you access to <A HREF="http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/" target="_parent">National Weather Service meterological data</A>.  There is also an online database that gives you INTERACTIVE visualization of climate data (Way cool!) and links to the World  Meteorological Data Center A.
</td>
</table>
<BR>

<table border=0 width=605>
<td>

<A HREF="images/s940330.gif" target="_parent" border=0><IMG SRC="images/el-nino.gif" width=180 BORDER=0></A><BR>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1>Sea Surface Variability </FONT></CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-2>(photo courtesy of NOAA/JPL/NASA)</FONT>
</td>
<td width=600>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>NOAA</STRONG> El Nino Home Page</FONT>
<BR>
NOAA also supports the <A HREF="http://www.pmel.noaa.gov/toga-tao/el-nino/home.html" target="_parent">El Nino Home Page</A>. 
This site gives you access to a lot of interesting information about the El Nino phenomena which is believed to affect weather patterns which steer tropical storms, influence drought cycles, and other weather anomalies.  Click on the photo at left to view a sample photo from the satellite photo data archives (3/30/94).  This home page links to more comprehensive data, including animated sequences.
</td>
</table>
<BR>

<table border=0 width=605>
<td>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/atwork2.gif" ><BR>
<B>Under Construction</B></CENTER><BR>
</td><BR>
<td width=600>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>UOG</STRONG> Guam Astronomical Home Page</FONT>
<BR>
The equatorial belt in the tropics is the only place on our planet where eight of the ten brightest stars 
in the universe can be seen.  Pam Eastlick of the University of Guam Planetarium will be providing star maps 
and other information to guide your search of the horizons (coming soon).  In the meantime, fans of the local scene can browse Pam's Web Page, <A HREF="http://bang.lanl.gov/solarsys/edu/moonio.htm" target="_parent">Luna and Io</A>, a comparative study of two moons of the planet Jupiter.
</td>
</table>
<BR>

<table border=0 width=605>
<td>
<CENTER><A HREF="images/TOMSmarch79_94.gif" target="_parent"><IMG SRC="images/ozone1.gif" BORDER=0></A><BR>
</td>
<td width=600>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>Ozone Depletion</STRONG></FONT><BR>
<BR>
There has been a lot of publicity regarding the apparent depletion of the Ozone layer by residual 
chemicals in the upper atmosphere.  This was first observed by the <A HREF="http://www.nbs.ac.uk/public/icd/ozone_pub/index.html" target="_parent">  British Antarctic Society</A> Home Page which gives an explanation of this phenomena.  NASA has been monitoring levels of ozone and other chemicals in the upper atmosphere and has an excellant Fact Page which describes <A HREF="http://spso.gsfc.nasa.gov/NASA_FACTS/ozone/ozone.html" target="_parent">what Ozone is and why do we care?</A> 
There is also an activist perspective which is detailed in the <A HREF="http://www.essential.org/orgs/Ozone_Action/1.html" target="_parent">
 Ozone Action </A>Home Page.  Click on the photo at left to view a copy of the comparison of satellite photos showing the progression of Ozone levels from 1979 to 1994.  The long term effects of this situation are not yet clear.  These sites are where the most recent information is available on the subject.  Thought you might like to know.<BR>
<BR>
</td>
</table>


<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/blineh8.gif" WIDTH="100%"><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:genmgr@ite.net"><I>genmgr@ite.net</I></A><br> 


</body>
</html>





