<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>
IT&E History
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="images/pebbl01.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000050" VLINK="#000000" ALINK="#990000">
<center>
<A NAME="top"></A><IMG SRC="images/histbar.gif"></center><BR><BR>
<center><A HREF="#1979">1979</A> <A HREF="#1983">1983</A> <A HREF="#1985">1985</A> <A HREF="#1986">1986</A> <A HREF="#1989">1989</A> <A HREF="#1990">1990</A> <A HREF="#1992">1992</A> <A HREF="#1993">1993</A> <A HREF="#1996">1996</A></center>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<table border=0 width=520>
<tr>
<td width=550>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A NAME="1979">1979</A> - Three innovative entrepreneurs join forces to form IT&E Corp: Jose D. Perez, John M. 
Borlas, and Jaime F. Tuquero.  IT&E focused on the sale and installation of business telephone systems.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="1983">1983</A> - IT&E begins its long distance operations offering direct dialing service to domestic points with rates reduced over 47% lower than its competitor.  IT&E, with its innovative approach, captured a major share of the domestic-bound markets, which divided the monopoly once held by the competition for over 30 years.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1985">1985</A> - IT&E introduces direct dialing service to international points at greatly reduced rates.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1986">1986</A> - Opening of IT&E Saipan office and began offering business telephone systems and long distance 
services.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1989">1989</A> - IT&E opens its first international gateway switching center allowing IT&E to achieve parity as a service 
provider with other telecommunications giants such as AT&T and MCI.  IT&E secures direct-service correspondent 
agreements with AT&T, KDD in Japan, PLDT in the Philippines, and DACOM in Korea extending its coverage to 
more than 280 countries and areas worldwide.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1990">1990</A> - IT&E and AT&T collaborate to offer the ECONO-CHARGE card, a joint long-distance telephone card allowing
 consumers to make long distance phone calls while traveling in Hawaii, the continental U.S. and other international 
destinations.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1992">1992</A> - IT&E becomes the first long-distance company on Guam and Saipan  to launch a long-distance discount plan. 
The Volume Incentive Plan (VIP) offered consumers automatic volume discounts.<BR>
<BR> 
<A NAME="1993">1993</A> - IT&E celebrates its 10th  Anniversary.  Also introduces the Right Plan, where double digit automatic savings
 are given to calls that cost the most.  IT&E installs its second gateway, a $5 million dollar AT&T digital international 
gateway switching system, the 5ESS paving the way for new technological benefits for Guam.<BR><BR>
<A NAME="1996">1996</A> - IT&E, today, continues to be Guams only locally owned, full service long distance telephone company.  IT&E 
credits the hardworking efforts of its employees who have kept the customer  first in all aspects of operations.  It is
 this innovative spirit and direction that will keep IT&E a forerunner in the telecommunications industry in the years 
to come.<BR><BR></FONT> 
</td>
</tr>
</table></CENTER>
<BR>
