<head>
<title>
Web Editors and making Web Pages
</title>
</head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="images/bsoup052.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#0000A0" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#00FF00">
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/edit.gif">
</center><BR><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/"><IMG SRC="images/netlog89.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0></A><H1>The Making of a Home Page</H1>
<CENTER><table border=0 width=520>
<td width=30> </td>
<td>
<A HREF="#EDITORS">[Editors]</A>
<A HREF="#HTML">[HTML]</A>
<A HREF="#Instant Home Page">[Instant Home Page]</A><BR>
<P>
<STRONG><B><BIG>So you've got this burning urge to see your name in Cyberspace. </BIG></B> You want your own web page.  Take my advice, don't do it.  There are over 50 million Web Pages out there already and growing.   More than 20,000 domain sites are added each day with dozens to hundreds of new pages in each domain.  Frankly, you could spend the rest of your life browsing through the Web and hardly scratch the surface.  The quantity of human knowledge already on the Web, or accessible through it, is staggering. But you don't care, this is your chance to debut before the whole world...<P>

<B><BIG>Look Mom, no hands!</BIG></B>  If you are going to the trouble and effort to make your own Web site, then (for our sake) put some thought into what you want to say.  Start with some reason why anyone, besides your mom, would want to visit your site.  If you can think of one or two, then by all means, do it.  Let's focus on some basics.  The World Wide Web is graphical.  It's possible to cruise the Web with a text browser, and remember the way the Web was.  But why bother?  The analogy is like going to a Hollywood premiere wearing earplugs and a blindfold. Yeah, the popcorn tastes good and you can feel the gum on the seat, but you're missing the big picture. Consider the really cool site sponsored by the Vatican that shows Michaelangelo's paintings in the Sistine Chapel (<A HREF="http://www.christusrex.org/">Christus Rex et Redemptor Mundi</A>).  Would you be satisfied to read a
bunch of scholarly writings on renaissance murals or would you prefer to have it as garnish for a beautiful collection of 325 photos of the famed chapel?  So we'll assume you'll be making Web pages intended to be seen as well as read.  Now to begin your quest, seek the holy grail of HTML...<P>

<A NAME="HTML"></A>
<B><BIG>Hypertext Markup Language (HTML). </BIG></B>The command structure of the Web is based on Unix.  PC and Mac operating systems are based on a subset of the command structure of Unix. Unix was chosen to provide the basic building blocks for the Internet primarily because it was written as a multi-platform open operating system and was supported by the large mainframe computers which dominated the landscape in the early days of computing.  The actual documents or "Web Pages" float on top of the operating system and are viewed through a browser which binds with the operating system on one hand, and interprets and displays the Web Pages on the other. Web pages are written in a simplified language that is a subset of SGML (Standard Graphical Markup Language), known as HTML.  HTML is a set of formatting specifications which consist of a set of simple bracketed commands, or "tags", which are embedded within the HTML file (Web Page). With wider acceptance, the HTML standard has been under increasing pressure to improve by adding new capabilities.  As more complex functions are added to the Web by the dominate browser makers, the actual specification is evolving much more rapidly than the current published standards adopted by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).  The W3C, the group responsible for setting HTML standards, has a long-standing motto: "We don't believe in Kings, Presidents, or voting; only rough consensus and running code". So far, Netscape has been making the best code and with 80% of the Web using Netscape Navigator, they set the de facto standard.  At present, HTML 2.0 is the current reference standard, and HTML 3.0 is under debate.  Many of the features proposed for HTML 3.0 have already been incorporated within the more popular web browsers and are usually referred to as HTML 2+ or HTML 3+ enhancements.  Now that you know enough to be a caller on the Practical Computing Show, lets get to it....<P>

<B><BIG>Home Page. </BIG></B> A home page is a starting point for your Web masterpiece.  The best part about the Web is that you can finally afford the home of your dreams. However, whole point of creating a page is to communicate your message.  The first step is to prepare, in rough form, the text, images and layout desired, as well as, the external documents (Web pages) you want to link to and any "mailto:" addresses you'd like to offer your readers.  The images must be in screen format (either GIF or JPEG format at 72 dpi resolution).  For your first time up at bat, keep it simple with one or two images.  Okay, time to get serious, you'll need some tools for this trip.....<P>

<B><BIG><A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/">The NCSA Home Page.</A></BIG></B>  The original graphical browser is Mosaic, written at NCSA (National Center for Supercomputing Applications) at the University of Illinois at Urbana.  Their Web site contains most of the documentation you need to get started with HTML editing and lot's of good answers for the newbie user.  Check out <A HREF="http://union.ncsa.uiuc.edu:80/HyperNews/get/www/html/guides.html"> Guides to Writing HTML Documents</A> for links to all of the current HTML reference standards and great how-to information.  HTML Writer's Guild (http://www.synet.net/hwg/index.html) is another gold mine of information on Web Page authoring. Two of the authors of the Mosaic program left the academic fold at NCSA and founded Netscape Communications, a public corporation that markets Netscape Navigator and other Web software. Their <A HREF="http://home.netscape.com/">Home Page</A> (http://home.netscape.com/) is worth visiting for the links to numerous resources on Web Page authoring and running server sites on the Internet.  They have provided enormous momentum in the expansion of the Web.  An announced version is scheduled to ship in March which will include HTML editing functions. <P>

<A NAME="Instant Home Page"></A>
<B><BIG>Instant Home Page.  </BIG></B><A HREF="http://www.mcli.dist.maricopa.edu/tut/">Writing HTML</A> is a site that coaches you on how to make your own Home Page.  This is a very good on-line tutor, but remember, you're paying for connect time.  Writing HTML won't make you an expert, but it will teach you the basics of building a solid homepage.  BestSeller has a number of novice HTML books in stock, some include basic HTML editors and tutorials. If you've gotten this far and are still convinced this is for you, my advice is to visit some sites, download an editor and try your hand at composing a few pages.  You can get a look at source code (a cool word for an HTML document) by opening a Web page with your favorite browser and saving it as "source".  Open any text editor to look at working code.  But this is primitive when you can get yourself a Web editor.... download one of the following packages and go through their built-in tutorial. <P>


<A NAME="EDITORS"></A>
<B><BIG>Editors.</BIG></B>  <A HREF="http://www.sq.com/">HoTMetal Pro</A>, <A HREF="http://www.nesbitt.com/">WebEdit</A>, <A HREF="http://www.sausage.com">HotDog Pro</A>, and <A HREF="http://lal.cs.byu.edu/people/nosack/">HTML Writer</A> are very powerful editors all of which support the HTML 3.0 standards.   Most are "downloadable" for a free 30 day trial run. At the end of the evaluation period, a software lock prevents program access until you have registered the software.  Their are at least a dozen editors available on the Web last time I looked.  Check out <A HREF="http://union.ncsa.uiuc.edu/HyperNews/get/www/html/editors.html"> Mag's Big List of HTML Editors</A>.   If your a Mac fiend on a tight budget, try the freeware program <A HREF="http://ogopogo.nttc.edu/tools/HTMLedit/HTMLedit.html">HTML.edit</A>.   After selecting an editor, the tutorial or instructions will explain the HTML tags  that are supported and how they are activated.  Most of the editors have a Home Page wizard which will help you break the ice. All editors will support images in Compuserve's GIF format, some allow JPEG format, which compresses larger pictures into a smaller file size with some loss of detail.  Text can be formatted as headings, simple statements or paragraphs.  The most powerful features of HTML lie in the capability to "link" or "anchor" text and images to points within the document or other, external documents.  It is this linkage capability that gives the Web it's name. Web Page composition is a topic we'll have to cover later. When your Web page is done you can check it out on a verification site to ensure it's composed according to the rules.  At that point, contact someone with a Web server  and have them hang your page out for all the  world to see.
<BR></STRONG>
<CENTER><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="images/go_top~1.gif" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Go to top of page</CENTER>
</td>
</table></CENTER>

