<html>
<head>
<title>HOLIDAY BLUES</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><img src="images/hwatcbnr.gif" align="bottom"
width="450" height="100">&#160;</p>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<div align="center"><center>
<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="640">
    <tr>
        <td align="center" valign="top" width="180"> 
        <p align="right">&#160; </p>
        <p align="left"><font color="#008000"><font size="5"><em><strong>About
        Holiday Blues...</strong></em></font><font size="3"><em><strong> </strong></em></font><em><strong>&#160; </strong></em></font></p>
        <ul>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a href="dodont.htm"><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong>Dos and
                Don'ts to Manage Holiday Blues </strong></font></font></a></p>
            </li>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a href="symptoms.htm"><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong>Symptoms
                of Holiday Blues</strong></font></font></a><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong> </strong></font></font><font
                color="#000000"><font size="2"><strong>&#160; </strong></font></font></p>
            </li>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a href="causes.htm"><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong>Causes of
                Holiday Blues</strong></font></font></a><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong> </strong></font></font></p>
            </li>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a href="sad.htm"><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong>Seasonal
                Affective Disorder</strong></font></font></a><font
                color="#0000FF"><font size="2"><strong> </strong></font></font></p>
            </li>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a
                href="http://www.med.nyu.edu/Psych/screens/depres.html"><font
                size="2"><strong>Depression Screening Test</strong></font></a><font
                size="2"> </font></p>
            </li>
            <li> 
                <p align="left"><a href="blsthera.htm"><font
                size="2"><em><strong>Holidays Can Be Therapeutic
                for Grieving Soul</strong></em> </font></a><br>
                <font size="2">-- the story of how one family
                celebrated the holidays after the death of their
                father</font> </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p align="left"><img src="images/xmas013.gif"
        align="bottom" width="146" height="150"> </p>
        </td>
        <td align="center" valign="top" width="10">&#160; 
        <p>&#160; </p>
        <p><img src="images/vertln40.gif" align="bottom"
        width="1" height="400"> </p>
        <p>&#160; </p>
        <p>&#160; </p>
        <p>&#160; </p>
        <p>&#160; </p>
        </td>
        <td valign="top" width="450"> 
        <p align="center"><font color="#000080"><font size="6"><b><img
        src="images/gifts.gif" align="left" hspace="10"
        vspace="5" width="150" height="112"></b></font></font><font
        color="#000080"><font size="6"><b>Holiday</b><em><b> </b></em><b>Blues</b></font><font
        size="5"><b><br>
        </b></font></font></p>
        <p>Holidays are supposed to be a joyful time of good
        cheer and optimistic hopes. Yet, it is not unusual for
        many of us to feel sad or lonely during the holiday
        period -- a condition that has come to be called <font
        color="#000080"><em><strong>holiday blues</strong></em></font>
        or <font color="#000080"><em><strong>holiday depression</strong></em></font>. </p>
        <p>Holiday depression may occur at any holiday or
        vacation time, but most commonly happens during the <font
        color="#000000">December holidays</font> when, it may
        seem, just about everyone in the world is celebrating in
        some way. There are many <a href="causes.htm">causes for
        holiday blues</a>, and the <a href="symptoms.htm">symptoms</a>
        may mimic clinical depression. <img
        src="images/cane012.gif" align="right" hspace="2"
        vspace="2" width="97" height="150"> </p>
        <p>While they may be intense and unsettling, holiday
        blues are usually short-lived, lasting for a few days to
        a few weeks prior to or just after the holiday. The good
        news is, <font color="#000000">holiday blues usually
        subside after the holiday season is over</font> and daily
        routines are resumed. </p>
        <p>There is a long list of recommended <a
        href="dodont.htm">Dos and Don'ts</a> for managing your
        holiday blues. The most important things to remember are:
        it's a normal response to a stress-filled time of the
        year, and you don't have to suffer unnecessarily. Find
        someone to talk with who can help you through this
        difficult time -- a family member, friend, member of the
        clergy, or <a href="../diabetes/teleserve.htm">a physician or
        professional counselor</a>. </p>
        <p>Holiday blues, although serious, should not be
        confused with another condition called <a href="sad.htm">Seasonal
        Affective Disorder</a>, which is a clinically diagnosed
        mood disorder that usually occurs during the winter
        months. </p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<hr>
