<title>Methodist Scoop - Astronauts</title><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">                               <!--body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b> Astronauts, Cosmonauts Undergo Tests at Methodist Following Historic Mission </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>Since the 1960s, the U.S. space program has led the world in space exploration and showcased the skill, dedication, and courage of its scientists and astronauts.  The recent linkup of the space shuttle Atlantis and the Russian Mir space station, along with the movie retelling of the Apollo 13 flight, have brought the unearthly heroics of these men and women back into public consciousness. <PBut while the public is drawn to the dramatic stories of human spirit, scientific achievement, teamwork, and international cooperation, they often overlook the more mundane - but extremely important - medical testing that is a significant part of each space mission.<p>For years the Texas Medical Center and The Methodist Hospital have been involved in medical research for NASA, and most recently, Methodist had a hand in the historic Atlantis/Mir mission completed in June.<p>Following years of preparation and, for some of the astronauts and cosmonauts, months in space, the space explorers are coming to Methodist to undergo a number of tests that will help determine how space travel - particularly weightlessness - affects the human body.<p>	When people go into space, the lack of gravity has profound physical effects.  Bone and muscle loss, which on Earth are caused by disuse, are some of the results of living in zero gravity for weeks or months at a time.<p>"Though the astronauts exercise in space," says Adrian LeBlanc, Ph.D., a medical physicist at Methodist, "it isn't sufficient to counteract the effects of weightlessness.  It's important to know not only what causes the loss, but also what can be done to regain bone and muscle back on Earth."<p>LeBlanc and Tom Hedrick, MD, a radiologist at Methodist, are using magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) to examine the expansion of intervertebral discs and changes in the leg and back muscles.  <p>LeBlanc also serves as co-investigator for test carried out at NASA to measure the decrease in bone mineral density of astronauts during the flight and the rate of recovery back on Earth.  In addition, the researchers are investigating how MRI can be used as a tool to study bone structure.<p>	Such research has important implications to the earthbound.  "These tests can help us understand and ultimately treat bone and muscle loss in the elderly, particularly as they relate to disuse," LeBlanc says.<p>	Similar tests are conducted on people who don't travel through the solar system for a living.  To experience conditions comparable to weightlessness, these terrestrials are required to stay in bed for up to 120 days at a time.<p>	The unique environment provided by the space program has led to some important medical breakthroughs, including the development of implantable defibrillators, similar to pacemakers, and the digital imaging technologies used in CAT and MRI.  LeBlanc adds that NASA has contributed to the development of bone densitometry, which is widely used in the diagnosis and treatment of osteoporosis.<p>	The Atlantis/Mir mission, which took LeBlanc to Russia to work with scientists and cosmonauts there, is not his first project with NASA; he was also involved in the Apollo and Sky Lab missions.<p>	In his experiences, LeBlanc has found the astronauts to be "all-American men and women - bright, motivated, and enthusiastic about what they do."<p>But he adds that they always seem to be glad to be back on Earth, especially after longer missions like Atlantis/Mir, which kept one American and two Russians in space for approximately four months.<p>Even a few days in space can cause significant changes in the body.  Astronauts become tired and the way they move is affected because the muscles one uses on Earth may not be the same muscles used in a weightless state.  LeBlanc is especially interested to examine the results of astronaut Norman Thagard's four month stay aboard Mir.<p>"It will be interesting to see what the physiological changes are after four months away from Earth," he says.<p>LeBlanc also notes that the astronauts are more than willing to aid in medical research, but sometimes want to know why they're being asked to undergo certain tests.  "They don't regard themselves as guinea pigs.  You have to convince them of the safety and significance of some procedures," he adds.<p>	Despite this occasional wariness about specific tests, the astronauts recognize the overall importance of medical research in space.<p>	"As the only governmental agency conducting human exploration in space, NASA is in the unique position to invest in advanced engineering and medical technology," LeBlanc says.  "Methodist is proud to contribute to NASA's medical research project".

<hr size=4><center><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
