<title>Methodist Scoop - Cardiac Evaluation Unit</title><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">   <!--body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b>Cardiac Evaluation Unit Brings Peace of Mind to Doctors and Patients </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>There are probably more enjoyable ways to spend 12 hours than as a patient in Methodist's emergency room, but many patients and physicians are finding that a short stay in the Emergency Department's Cardiac Evaluation Unit (CEU) can save time, money, and possibly lives.<p>	Before the CEU was established in November 1994, ER patients experiencing heart attack symptoms usually had two options:  to be sent to a cardiac care unit (CCU) for a minimum of 24 hours, or to be sent home although their conditions may have been more serious than originally thought.  Physicians often faced the dilemma of providing too much care in the CCU or too little by discharging the patient.<p>	The Cardiac Evaluation Unit has eliminated those difficult choices, offering an intermediate care setting that allows for more complete patient evaluations by physicians before they decide to admit or discharge a patient.<p>	Because Methodist is  known as an excellent cardiac care hospital, its emergency room is the first choice for many people who think they are having heart attacks.  Each day, Emergency Department employees see patients experiencing chest pains and other heart attack symptoms.  Only about one-third of those people, however, are actually having heart attacks; the others may be suffering from any number of problems, including unstable angina, embolisms, or pulmonary or gastrointestinal ailments.  <p>	In the past, physicians would make a fairly rapid evaluation in the ER and, with just a preliminary "snapshot", decide whether it was safe to send a patient home or if he or she needed to be admitted to the CCU for further observation.  Often, neither seemed like a perfect plan.  While the doctor may have wanted the patient to undergo more tests, an expensive stay in the CCU may not have been warranted.  On the other hand, nobody wanted to risk the possibly tragic consequences of premature discharge.<p>	The monitored beds of the Cardiac Evaluation Unit, located within the Emergency Room, have reduced that risk, allowing physicians to observe patients for up to 24 hours, though most CEU stays generally last between six and 12 hours.  In that time, caregivers can learn enough about a patient's health to make an appropriate, unhurried decision.<p>In observing CEU patients, caregivers often use a relatively new process developed by Methodist cardiologists.  The CK subforms test is a procedure that looks at a person's enzymes to see if a heart attack has occurred.  Similar tests used to take six to 12 hours; the CK subforms test takes as little as four hours for diagnosis.<p>	In addition to the test, CEU staff also take into account patient history and EKG readings.  With these and other indicators, caregivers can get a relatively complete picture of a patient's health in a short period of time. <p>"Physicians like the idea that they can observe a patient and make a decision based on more than just a preliminary snapshot," says Robert Fromm, M.D., Chief of Emergency Services at Methodist.<p>	"Patients like it, too," adds Johnie Leonard, R.N., Manager of the Emergency Department.  "They feel comfortable being discharged if they've had an opportunity to be observed first." <p>	Patients also appreciate the difference in price.  Bed space alone in the cardiac care unit is $1,000 a day.  A few hours in the CEU is considerably less, and it was with cost savings and increased efficiency in mind that the unit was created.<p>"There are tremendous cost-saving advantages and decreases in unnecessary admissions.  The unit can reduce the burden on the CCU and telemetry units in the hospital," says Leonard.<p>	The CEU is now seeing approximately six patients a week, though Leonard says it can handle a greater capacity.  "We're hoping that doctors will use it more and more, especially with the current ICU bed crunch."<p>For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
