<title>Methodist Scoop - Felix</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b>Felix the Feline Therapist is a Hit with Patients </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>Happy Birthday, Felix...He's the black and white feline therapist at the hospital's Rehabilitation Center.  June 21 was his birthday, or his assigned birthday by Center employees, because that's the day Felix was approved by the Infection Control Committee to live (and work) in the Rehab Center.<p>	"We know he's about five years old," says Denise Mosgrove, CRT specialist, who was instrumental in bringing Felix to Methodist.  "We got him from Teri Boyd's kennel in Tomball after his owner had to give him up due to a family transfer.  Now he acts like he owns the place.  Everyone loves Felix; he's sort of famous.  People will see him and say hi to him before they'll say hi to the person walking him on his leash.  Elevator passengers have asked me, 'is that Felix?'  He's even done an interview on KIKK about the use of animals in patient therapy.  He was mobbed."<p>Specifically, while on his job, Felix will help patients become more comfortable expressing their feelings, show and receive some attention and affection, even work with motor skills by playing games with him.<p>"The Kitty Teaser is what we call the fishing game because it looks like a fishing pole and patients cast and move the pole to involve Felix," says Mosgrove.  "Many patients will use cognitive processing to develop a strategy to play the game with Felix."<p>	Felix's house is the large room called "Therapeutic Recreation."  He prefers to sleep in a chair or on a pool table.  In the mornings he takes his walk down the hallways to visit patients.  Early afternoon is his rest time, then late afternoon he's on the prowl with patients again.<p>And Felix has been know to get into some mischief.<p>"He used to open up all the cabinets every night," says Mosgrove, still smiling.  "And then there was the time he jumped into the basketball free throw game we have set up for patients and brought it crashing down."  Take that, Shaq.<p>Felix also managed to get behind the wheel of the rehab car in the Center's gym area.  He crawled through a lowered window and was ready to go joy riding with Toonces, but was discovered before he could figure out that the Taurus has no tires.<p>Felix's innovative role at the Center is part of a program called animal-assisted therapy, dating back to 1792 at the York Retreat in England.  Almost a century later, in 1897, Germany used animals to help treat epileptic patients.  In the U.S., Boris Levinson in 1958 began using his dog Jingles to help disturbed children.  Now there is even an award named after Jingles given each year to a dog who has done an exceptional job of helping in patient therapy.<p>By the way, Felix loves visitors, but isn't permitted outside the Rehab Center on main 5.  Weekends are spent with staff members.<p>"Felix has turned a lot of people into cat lovers around here," says Mosgrove.  "We have a long list of people offering to take him if we ever had to do that.  We'd prefer that it remain just a wish list.  He's pretty lovable."<p>For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
