<title>Methodist Scoop - ICU</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b> New Fondren ICU Design Includes Patient Suggestions </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>When it came time to refurbish a key intensive care unit (ICU) at The Methodist Hospital, the unit's head nurse enlisted the advice of experts.<p>Nurse Fe Cuano talked to doctors, nurses, ward clerks and nursing assistants on what features the new unit should have.  But most important, she sought the advice of patients.<p>Nearly three years later, Cuano helped cut the ribbon to officially re-open her nursing unit in the Fondren-Brown building at Methodist and welcomed 10 patients to the unit on its first working day.<p>Cuano is head nurse of the cardio-thoracic ICU, where patients recover from major thoracic surgeries such as cardiovascular and transplant procedures.  Cuano and her staff are happy with the new unit, which opened June 19, because they know it was refurbished from the ceiling tiles down according to their own specifications.<p>"Although the renovation work on the old Fondren ICU started in November of last year, the actual planning goes back to 1992," she says.  'And an important part of it was tracking patient comments over the years to see what features we could incorporate into a new unit."<p>So those who attended the June 16 grand opening saw a sparkling 30-bed unit boasting state-of-the-art monitoring and support equipment in brighter, more colorful surroundings.<p>One patient-friendly touch is the inclusion of some stained-glass lighting fixtures in the unit's rooms.  "That was something we heard from patients - that we needed artwork" says Cuano.  "We told that to the architects and they came up with that suggestion."<p>Nurses also suggested to the designers that ceiling tiles over patient beds should be plain, with no design cut into them.  Patients coming out of anesthesia or who were bedridden for long periods told nurses when they stared at the old unit's ceiling, the designs in the tiles turned into "ants" that crawled.<p>"So we made sure that the tiles over the beds are plain," says Cuano, "but they have the typical designs in the hallway ceilings for those who like that kind of thing."<p>On a unit that cost approximately $5.5 million to renovate, Cuano concedes those are minor touches.  But they are important to patient satisfaction, and therefore important to the unit's planners.  "Everything on this unit," she adds, "emphasizes patient satisfaction."<p>The old ICU - built in 1965 - had 49 beds and problems with patient crowding.  What were 10-bed units in the old ICU were turned into six-bed wards to allow for more space.<p>Each bed has a bedside computer terminal for "paperless" record keeping and timely updating of patients information.  Closed circuit TV cameras over each bed allow nurses to keep around-the-clock eye on patients, and six glassed-in-rooms allow for pressure control and maximum visibility to nursing staff.<p>This renovation was a bit more complicated than most, because a number of other projects had to be completed before the ICU opened.  These included the installation of a new generator in the Fondren building, replacement of medical gas systems, and the construction of an exhaust system.<p>"It was a lot of work, but the end result was well worth it," says Cuano.  "Right now, I'm happy.  I'm smiling."<p>For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
