<title>Methodist Scoop - New Treatment for Brain Aneurysms</title>  <bodybgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg>
<h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b>New Treatment for Brain Aneurysms</b></font><hr size=6></h1></center>
<P>
Physicians at The Methodist Hospital in Houston are now able to treat patients who have dangerous brain aneurysms using a platinum coil device.<BR>
<P>
The Guglielmi Detachable Coil (GDC) is the first product to receive market clearance from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for this type of treatment.<BR>
<P>
The Methodist Hospital was one of the 20 hospitals nationwide that participated in the GDC clinical trials prior to FDA market clearance.<BR>
<P>
Nearly 40,000 people in the United States are diagnosed each year with brain aneurysms.  In approximately 25 percent of these cases, the aneurysm is deemed either inoperable or at high risk for surgical repair due to its location, anatomy, and/or the overall medical condition of the patient.<BR>
<P>
"This new technology offers hope to patients who risk losing their lives due to ruptured aneurysms that can cause hemorrhagic stroke," said Dr. Michel E. Mawad, director of Neuroradiology at The Methodist Hospital and principal investigator in the clinical trials.<BR>
<P>
Intracranial aneurysms are weak, balloon-like defects that protrude from arterial walls within the brain.  They can rupture, causing death or serious disability or can cause symptoms such as severe headache and dizziness when non-ruptured.<BR>
<P>
According to the National Stroke Association, stroke is the nation's third leading cause of death, resulting in 150,000 deaths every year.  Stroke risk increases with age, with the risk doubling after age 55.  For adults over age 65, the risk of dying from stroke is seven times that of the general population.<BR>
<P>
The GDC is a soft platinum alloy micro-coil that is delivered to the aneurysm site by a micro-catheter in a controlled manner.  It is detached and released into the aneurysm by application of a very low voltage electrical current.  Once in place, the GDC coil fills the aneurysm, isolating it from circulation and thereby reducing the likelihood of a rupture and hemorrhagic stroke.<BR>
<P>
"The GDC is a significant step forward in the development of new techniques to fight stroke," said Gary Houser, vice president of the National Stroke Association.  "A new paradigm of care is emerging for the treatment of neurological disease leading to stroke.  This includes the development of innovative new therapies such as the Guglielmi Detachable Coil, thrombolytic drugs, and neuroprotective compounds."<BR>
<P>
GDC coils have been used to treat approximately 1,200 people in the United States under an investigational device exemption.  Approximately 4,600 patients were treated outside the United States as well.  And Mawad has treated over 200 patients at The Methodist Hospital in Houston.<BR>
<P>
For more information about your specific health plan and services offered at The Methodist Hospital, call (713) 790-3333.	
