<title>Methodist Scoop - Midwives</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b>Midwives Lend High-Touch Technique to Birth Process </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>   	When she was a labor and delivery nurse at Methodist, Nell Sagehorn was accustomed to seeing women surrounded by doctors, nurses, and state-of-the-art technology when it came time to have a baby.<p>	So when it was time for Nell to have her first child, she used one of the most advanced high-tech instruments available today - the telephone.<p>	During her 12-hour labor Nell frequently talked over the phone with a nurse-midwife.  She advised Nell on how much to walk, whether or not to eat, how much to sleep.  Then when it was time to deliver the baby, the nurse-midwife met Nell and her doctor at the hospital and stayed with Nell until the birth of her son.<p>	Nell chose a "low-tech" route to have her baby because she wanted to have the experience naturally.  That was possible because she employed a certified nurse-midwife from a new service currently available at Methodist.<p>	Operated by Women's Specialists of Houston, the service is the first private-practice midwifery program to be given delivery privileges at a Texas Medical Center hospital.  The group includes two certified nurse-midwives, Audrey McCuyer and Mavis Schorn, and four board-certified obstetrician/gynecologists:  Mark Gottesman, MD; Meredith Morgan, MD; Terry Simon, MD; and Edward Yosowitz, MD.  Another midwifery program sponsored by Baylor College of Medicine has been in place at Methodist since 1991.<p>	At first Sagehorn wanted to have a conventional hospital-doctor delivery.  But she changed her mind after consulting with Gottesman.<p>	"I realized that I would get much more if a nurse-midwife worked with my doctor on the delivery," Sagehorn recalls.  "I decided I wanted the experience of a natural childbirth with a nurse-midwife...I heard it said that a doctor is high-tech, but a midwife is high-touch."<p>	Sagehorn met with nurse-midwife Mavis Schorn on a routine prenatal visit to her doctor's office.  Schorn followed the progress of Sagehorn and her baby, and when Sagehorn finally went into labor she called the nurse-midwife.<p>	Schorn and Gottesman worked as a team in the delivery room.  "It's called 'co-managing' the pregnancy and delivery," says Schorn, who has been a certified nurse-midwife for five years.  "The nurse-midwife takes the mother through the routine parts of labor and delivery, and an obstetrician is available to handle high--risk cases or difficult deliveries."<p>	"Our approach is to help the human body do what it is naturally supposed to do during childbirth," says Schorn.<p>	Because nurse-midwives help and coach a mother in labor, some fathers may think their role during childbirth may be limited.<p>	"We just try to help him help her," explains Schorn.  "We're not there to take his place."<p>	Sagehorn agrees.  'Mavis helped me by making suggestions about changing position, walking, things like that," she says.  "My husband was still very important in coaching me through the whole process."  <p>The practice of midwifery, or assisting in a childbirth, has been around for centuries.  Midwives handle low-risk deliveries of mothers with no serious medical problems.  They spend a lot of time with women before delivery, educating them about diet, exercise, and prenatal care.  They help women through the birth process, helping to coach the mother during labor and making sure the baby is healthy.  And midwives conduct postnatal care for both mother and child.<p>	Midwives are nurse practitioners, which are nurses with advanced degrees and specialized training.  At Methodist, approved midwives can admit patients to the hospital.  <p>	Midwifery is one of the most steadily growing nurse practitioner fields in the country.  There are approximately 3,900 female and male midwives in clinical practice in the United States.  All of them are certified by the American College of Nurse-Midwives.<p>	The growing trend has in some cases threatened physicians who believe only medical doctors can give the proper care to pregnant women.<p>	"I believe that working with midwives has made me a better clinician." says Gottesman.  "The idea of midwives may conjure up images of your great-grandmother delivering babies at home, and patients may worry that they'll receive less care if they see a midwife.  But once they meet the nurse midwives we work with, patients realize it's enhanced care with more depth than I can provide alone."<p>	At the Women's Specialists of Houston, patients who wish to work with a nurse-midwife see the midwife on their initial obstetrical visit.  Because nurse-midwives can have longer, more personalized visits, Gottesman says the mother can get more information she can use.<p>	"Then, as the pregnancy progresses, patient and midwife work together for routine pre-natal care," he continues.  "Unless it's a high-risk pregnancy or one with any kind of medical complications, the physician may see the patient just a few times until the delivery."	Gottesman says the new midwifery program is modeled after an Atlanta program with a very high successful labor and delivery record.<p>	"Each clinician brings something very valuable to the birth experience," he adds.  For the patient, it's a win-win situation."<p> For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
<p align=center>| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/about/index.html">Get To Know Us</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/ailing/index.html">What's Ailing You</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/health/index.html">Health Watch</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/magazine/index.html">Page Turners</a> |<br>
| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/manage/index.html">Managing Your Care</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/resource/index.html">On-line Resources</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/survey/index.html">Can We Talk</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/search/index.html">Search Our Site</a> |</p>
