<title>Methodist Scoop - Mother</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b> One Mother's Message is her Son's Legacy </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>	Teri Medina always had high hopes for her son Frank.  She figured he'd do something important someday, something that would help people.<p>One good sign was the sense of responsibility that 15-year-old Frank apparently had - he took a job at a McDonald's so he could buy his own car insurance.<p>	But one night, robbers forced their way into the restaurant after it had closed.  They beat Frank with baseball bats.  Medina rushed to Methodist, where Frank was taken, and stayed with her son until he was declared brain dead 12 days later.<p>Nearly a year later Medina stood before a large crowd in Methodist's Wiess Chapel and told them her son is changing people's lives, like she always thought he would.<p>"Three people benefited from Frank's organs," said Medina, a mother of four.  "I heard from one of them, a middle-aged woman named Patsy who received a kidney transplant.  She told me 'I can go grocery shopping again.'"<p>Medina joined others who shared their stories at the annual Service of Thanksgiving and Remembrance at Methodist, held April 19 as part of Organ and Tissue Donation Awareness Week.  And like Medina's, some of these were stories of mothers and their children.<p>Bobbie Schaefer came to the ceremony and told people about her son.  He was accepted into the U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis one day before he was killed in an accident.<p>"His eye test for Annapolis showed he had perfect vision," Schaefer remembered.  "He told me if anything ever happened to him, make sure those ol' peepers went to somebody who needed them.  And his corneas are helping someone to see right now."<p>	Even though the list of people who need organ transplants is growing, the chronic shortage of organs is growing worse.  One reason is that most Americans still do not understand the process of organ donation, according to Pat McCue, assistant manager of Methodist's Multi-Organ Transplant Center.<p>"Because of that, the responsibility of health care professionals to inform families of potential donors about the process of organ donation becomes even more acute," she said.<p>Figures supplied by the United Network for Organ Sharing (UNOS) show that, by the end of February, 38,364 patients were on waiting lists for organs nationwide.<p>But less than half will actually receive a transplant because on the average fewer than 5,000 people donate organs each year.  And since some donors supply more than one organ, approximately 15,000 people receive transplants annually.<p>There are many ways to learn about transplantation and organ donation.  Call the Methodist Multi-Organ Transplant Center at 790-2501 to find out more about transplants.  For more information on organ donation, call LifeGift at 799-9115, or UNOS at 1-800-24-DONOR.<p> For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
<p align=center>| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/about/index.html">Get To Know Us</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/ailing/index.html">What's Ailing You</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/health/index.html">Health Watch</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/magazine/index.html">Page Turners</a> |<br>
