<title>Methodist Scoop - Rhodes</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b> Rhodes' Typical Day Becomes a Piece of American History </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>	Lisa Rhodes never thought she'd be singled out for being typical, but that's exactly what happened when she was asked to join 22 other women from across the United States in celebrating the 75th anniversary of the Women's Bureau of the U.S. Department of Labor.<p>	On May 19 Rhodes, an EEG technologist at Methodist, and the other working women became a part of history when tokens of their daily lives were preserved in a time capsule at the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, D.C.<p>	The time capsule, called "Voices of Working Women," will be opened in the year 2020, on the 100th anniversary of the Women's Bureau.  The women submitted photos, narratives, and objects that tell something about their typical workdays.<p>Rhodes is the only woman from Texas included in the anniversary celebration.  She sent photos of herself on the job, performing EEGs on babies less than one month old for a research project, and other symbols of her work including a set of electrodes, and an EEG tracing.<p>She also sent pictures of herself at home with her family and, like the others represented in the time capsule, a letter to future working women and a journal of her day.  Rhodes says writing the journal was one of the most interesting parts of the project and it made her realize how much she accomplishes in a single day.<p>	"My day begins," she wrote, "with a sputter at 5 a.m., when I let our dog outside.  I then cuddle with my children, hoping it is Saturday.  The odds are against me...My uniform is a set of green scrubs...My husband will call me around 7:30 a.m. to make sure I am awake.  We are very fortunate that our child care provider lives across the street.  I leave my children in a loving and stimulating environment.  This enables me to feels secure about my desire to work."<p>Rhodes modestly says she was chosen simply because she met certain demographics - as the anniversary date grew closer, the Bureau needed a representative from Texas, as well as a Hispanic and a working mother, she says.  <p>Eli Mizrahi, MD, Rhodes' clinical supervisor, indirectly learned about the project and nominated Rhodes for the honor.<p>Because she was selected only a few weeks before the ceremony, Rhodes acted quickly to get everything together for the time capsule.  So the prestige of begin chosen to represent not only Texas but also the health care industry didn't immediately sink in.<p>"In the beginning it was all so bizarre and funny, I really didn't realize the impact it would have," she says.  "Then I was talking to my husband about it and thought, 'Oh my God, this is going to be in the Smithsonian!'"<p>At first Rhodes was unaware of who would also be contributing to the project.  "When I heard that is was only 23 women, I thought, 'Wow, that's a lot.'"<p>Despite their relatively few numbers, the participants come from a wide variety of careers and backgrounds.  In addition to Rhodes, there are teachers, truck drivers, ministers, farmers and the CEO of Paramount Pictures.  Although Rhodes couldn't go to the presentation at the White House, she is proud and excited that her daily achievements - however "typical" they may be - have earned her a place in history.  <p> <center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
<p align=center>| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/about/index.html">Get To Know Us</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/ailing/index.html">What's Ailing You</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/health/index.html">Health Watch</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/magazine/index.html">Page Turners</a> |<br>
| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/manage/index.html">Managing Your Care</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/resource/index.html">On-line Resources</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/survey/index.html">Can We Talk</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/search/index.html">Search Our Site</a> |</p>
