<title>Methodist Scoop - Telemed</title>                               <body bgcolor=#ffffff><center><img src=/methodist/scoop/scoop.jpg><h1><hr size=6><font size=+3><b>The Future of Medicine, Coming to a Television Screen Near You </b></font><hr size=6></h1></center><p>When urologist Peter Scardino scrubbed for a morning operation Wednesday, he was preparing for a routine prostatectomy.  But for 800 physicians gathered on the other side of the world, it was a major event.<p>The surgery from Methodist's Main 3 OR Wednesday was beamed via satellite to a meeting of the Italian Urologic Society.  The doctors, gathered in Rome, saw Scardino remove a cancerous prostate gland on live television and were able to talk to the surgeon while he performed the procedure.<p>When he was able to divert his attention from the surgery, Scardino could also see the physicians as he answered their questions over a second satellite hookup.  <p>This is the future of medicine - interactive video that has moved from the game room to the operating room.  Telemedicine, as it is called, is still in its infancy but when the practice becomes common it could revolutionize health care.<p>"This is the future of medicine," says Michael DeBakey, MD, senior attending surgeon at Methodist and chancellor of Baylor College of Medicine.  "It will extend our reach to virtually any place on Earth."<p>Although satellite communications technology has been available for decades, telemedicine has been slow to develop until now.  DeBakey thinks that one reason has been that, until recent years, doctors and hospitals were unwilling to participate in something that seemed extremely expensive.<p>"Technology has improved to the point where equipment is miniaturized and fairly standard," he explains.  "Now it's economically feasible to participate in telemedicine because it makes effective health care available to more people"	In 1965, DeBakey participated in the first intercontinental two-way broadcast of a heart surgery.  He did it partially to demonstrate the features of "Early Bird," the country's first commercial communications satellite, and partially to show the possibilities of telemedicine.  <p>Scardino, chief of Urology at Methodist and Baylor, believes that intercontinental exchanges such as his surgery this week will help take medical knowledge to new places.  "The Italians, for example, haven't traditionally treated prostate cancer with surgical methods," he explains.  "So this is a way to show them the most modern techniques in a very efficient way."<p>Wouldn't it be easier to just fly to Italy and perform a prostatectomy their?<p>"In the first place, 800 people wouldn't be able to see it because we couldn't fit them all into the operating room," replies Scardino.  "We'd still have to put it on television, probably over a closed-circuit system, to get the same result."<p>Scardino adds that having the patient, surgeon, staff, and conditions here at Methodist is the best way to show the proper methods.  "Because they're not used to the surgery, you're not going to have the facilities and staff on hand to recreate those ideal conditions," he says.<p>With DeBakey's help, private companies as well as the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) have collaborated to build a special telemedicine station at Methodist and Baylor.<p>The Medtel system is a video/computer linkup that will allow doctors here to communicate with, examine, and diagnose patients anywhere in the world.  A control center in DeBakey's Alkek Tower offices allows for linkup to the distant sites.<p>Initially, a special examination room was set up at Methodist, equipped with cameras and other diagnostic equipment that were operated by doctors in other areas for simulated testing of the equipment.<p>DeBakey says this system is more than just two-way video and audio communications and connection.  State-of-the-art electronics enable doctors to transmit and receive computerized information over telephone lines, as well as microwave and satellite links.<p>"Using the system we can instantaneously receive or send all sorts of information, such as an EKG or a blood pressure reading," he adds.  "And the video quality is so good that we could study X-rays over the system or even visually assess a patient's condition if we need to."<p>The Medtel system is privately owned and operated, and doctors or hospitals who wish to use it would make financial arrangements with the company that owns the system.<p>The procedure this week with Scardino did not utilize the Medtel system.  Satellite dishes and equipment from a number of outside companies made the connection possible.<p>DeBakey says telemedicine can eventually benefit remote areas where specialists are sparse, and can extend the reach of teaching institutions which can train doctors and technicians in other countries.  A setup like the Medtel system could also eventually be used by NASA to perform medical examinations on astronauts in a U.S. space station.<p>"We haven't even begun to consider all of the uses of telemedicine," says DeBakey.  "The possibilities are endless." <p> For more information contact <!a href=mailto:webmaster@methodist.com>webmaster@methodist.com</a><center><hr size=4><A HREF="/~imagemap/mhsmall"><IMG SRC="/methodist/icon/m-menu.gif" ISMAP border=0></a>
<p align=center>| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/about/index.html">Get To Know Us</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/ailing/index.html">What's Ailing You</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/health/index.html">Health Watch</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/magazine/index.html">Page Turners</a> |<br>
| <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/manage/index.html">Managing Your Care</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/resource/index.html">On-line Resources</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/survey/index.html">Can We Talk</a> | <a href="http://www.methodisthealth.com/search/index.html">Search Our Site</a> |</p>
<p align=center><a href="mailto:mailto:SBarnes@tmhother.tmh.tmc.edu">webmaster@methodisthealth.com</a> </p>
